WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.640 --> 00:00:02.080
PROFESSOR ROBERT SHILLER: OK.

00:00:02.080 --> 00:00:05.100
Welcome to Economics 252.

00:00:05.100 --> 00:00:08.115
This is Financial Markets,
and I'm Robert Shiller.

00:00:10.790 --> 00:00:14.840
This is a course for
undergraduates.

00:00:14.840 --> 00:00:19.830
It doesn't presume any
prerequisites except the basic

00:00:19.830 --> 00:00:20.840
Intro Econ
[Introductory Economics]

00:00:20.840 --> 00:00:22.660
prerequisite.

00:00:22.660 --> 00:00:24.720
It's about --

00:00:24.720 --> 00:00:28.650
well, the title of the course
is Financial Markets.

00:00:31.540 --> 00:00:34.090
By putting "markets" in the
title of the course, I'm

00:00:34.090 --> 00:00:37.920
trying to indicate that it's
down to earth, it's about the

00:00:37.920 --> 00:00:45.520
real world, and, well, to me it
connotes that this is about

00:00:45.520 --> 00:00:47.930
what we do with our lives.

00:00:47.930 --> 00:00:49.310
It's about our society.

00:00:49.310 --> 00:00:54.730
So, you might imagine it's a
course about trading since it

00:00:54.730 --> 00:00:59.710
says "markets," but it's
more general than that.

00:00:59.710 --> 00:01:03.050
Finance, I believe, is, as
it says in the course

00:01:03.050 --> 00:01:06.610
description, a pillar of
civilized society.

00:01:06.610 --> 00:01:10.410
It's the structure through which
we do things, at least

00:01:10.410 --> 00:01:13.660
on a large scale of things.

00:01:13.660 --> 00:01:16.700
It's about allocating resources
through space and

00:01:16.700 --> 00:01:21.630
time, our limited resources
that we have in our world.

00:01:21.630 --> 00:01:24.250
It's about incentivizing
people to

00:01:24.250 --> 00:01:27.970
do productive things.

00:01:27.970 --> 00:01:31.690
It's about sponsoring ventures
that bring together a lot of

00:01:31.690 --> 00:01:35.610
people and making sure that
people are fairly treated,

00:01:35.610 --> 00:01:38.680
that they contribute
constructively and that they

00:01:38.680 --> 00:01:41.400
get a return for doing that.

00:01:41.400 --> 00:01:44.640
And it's about managing risks,
that anything that we do in

00:01:44.640 --> 00:01:46.270
life is uncertain.

00:01:46.270 --> 00:01:49.530
Anything big or important
that we do is uncertain.

00:01:49.530 --> 00:01:54.770
And to me that's what financial
markets is about.

00:02:00.240 --> 00:02:05.620
To me, this is a course that
will have a philosophical

00:02:05.620 --> 00:02:10.180
underpinning, but at the
same time will be

00:02:10.180 --> 00:02:11.970
very focused on details.

00:02:15.930 --> 00:02:19.950
I'm fascinated by the details
about how things work.

00:02:19.950 --> 00:02:23.840
It can be boring, and I hope I'm
not boring in this course,

00:02:23.840 --> 00:02:29.480
but it's in the details
that things happen.

00:02:29.480 --> 00:02:32.500
So, I want to talk about
particular institutions, and

00:02:32.500 --> 00:02:35.820
I'm interpreting finance
broadly in this course.

00:02:35.820 --> 00:02:39.000
I want to talk about
banking, insurance.

00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:42.300
Sometimes people don't include
insurance as part of finance,

00:02:42.300 --> 00:02:46.440
but I don't see why not,
so we'll include it.

00:02:46.440 --> 00:02:49.800
It's about securities, about
futures markets, about

00:02:49.800 --> 00:02:52.190
derivatives markets, and
it's going to be

00:02:52.190 --> 00:02:54.990
about financial crises.

00:02:54.990 --> 00:02:57.200
And it's also about
the future.

00:02:57.200 --> 00:02:59.240
I like to try to think about
the future, although

00:02:59.240 --> 00:03:01.830
it's hard to do so.

00:03:01.830 --> 00:03:03.800
Where are we going?

00:03:03.800 --> 00:03:07.520
This course will have a U.S.
bias since we live in the

00:03:07.520 --> 00:03:09.610
United States.

00:03:09.610 --> 00:03:12.950
I know the U.S. better than any
other country, but at the

00:03:12.950 --> 00:03:18.160
same time, I recognize that many
of you, or even most of

00:03:18.160 --> 00:03:24.510
you, will work outside the U.S.,
and so it's important

00:03:24.510 --> 00:03:27.100
that we have a world
perspective, which is

00:03:27.100 --> 00:03:32.470
something I will try my utmost
to incorporate in this course.

00:03:32.470 --> 00:03:36.140
The world perspective also
particularly matters since we

00:03:36.140 --> 00:03:39.200
have other viewers for this
course besides those

00:03:39.200 --> 00:03:41.460
people in this room.

00:03:41.460 --> 00:03:47.230
This course is one of a couple
dozen courses that Yale

00:03:47.230 --> 00:03:51.470
University is offering
free to the world as

00:03:51.470 --> 00:03:54.860
part of Open Yale.

00:03:54.860 --> 00:03:57.940
And that means there's
a cameraman back

00:03:57.940 --> 00:03:59.690
there if you've noticed.

00:03:59.690 --> 00:04:03.820
That's Dan Cody filming
the course.

00:04:03.820 --> 00:04:08.790
And it will be eventually posted
on the internet and it

00:04:08.790 --> 00:04:12.440
will be available through
Open Yale, and then by

00:04:12.440 --> 00:04:14.830
proliferation, you'll
find it on many

00:04:14.830 --> 00:04:18.730
other websites as well.

00:04:18.730 --> 00:04:21.390
This is the second time
this course has been

00:04:21.390 --> 00:04:22.735
filmed for Open Yale.

00:04:22.735 --> 00:04:28.560
The first time was in 2008,
three years ago.

00:04:28.560 --> 00:04:35.020
And I'm very pleased to report
that I have a lot of people in

00:04:35.020 --> 00:04:40.150
every imaginable country who
have watched these lectures.

00:04:40.150 --> 00:04:44.440
And I get emails from them, so I
know that they're out there.

00:04:48.230 --> 00:04:51.240
But I thought that this course
needs updating, probably more

00:04:51.240 --> 00:04:53.820
than any course on Open Yale.

00:04:53.820 --> 00:04:57.170
You know, a course in physics
only has to be updated for the

00:04:57.170 --> 00:04:59.990
last three years of research in
physics, and it's probably

00:04:59.990 --> 00:05:03.495
not a big thing for an
undergraduate course.

00:05:03.495 --> 00:05:09.070
But finance really has to be
updated, I think, because it's

00:05:09.070 --> 00:05:12.260
going through such turmoil
and change right now.

00:05:12.260 --> 00:05:15.620
We've had the worst financial
crisis since the Great

00:05:15.620 --> 00:05:19.150
Depression, and it's been
a worldwide crisis.

00:05:19.150 --> 00:05:23.100
And governments around the world
are working on changing

00:05:23.100 --> 00:05:25.760
our financial institutions.

00:05:25.760 --> 00:05:30.320
We have organizations of
governments, notably the G-20,

00:05:30.320 --> 00:05:32.080
which is very involved
in finance.

00:05:32.080 --> 00:05:35.500
It's one of the top items on
their agenda for international

00:05:35.500 --> 00:05:39.290
cooperation, it's changing
our financial markets.

00:05:39.290 --> 00:05:42.180
So, I think that that's another
reason why I want to

00:05:42.180 --> 00:05:49.280
try to keep as international a
focus as I'm good at doing in

00:05:49.280 --> 00:05:51.590
this course.

00:05:51.590 --> 00:05:55.300
But I hope that those of you who
are in this room are not

00:05:55.300 --> 00:06:02.470
disturbed by the camera and feel
you can ask questions.

00:06:02.470 --> 00:06:04.510
You don't have to
be on camera.

00:06:04.510 --> 00:06:05.840
I think I'm just being filmed.

00:06:09.350 --> 00:06:13.270
So, that's where we are.

00:06:13.270 --> 00:06:18.220
Now, I wanted to put this in a
little bit broader context.

00:06:18.220 --> 00:06:23.280
The other major finance course
that we have here at Yale is

00:06:23.280 --> 00:06:30.010
Economics 251 and it's taught by
Professor John Geanakoplos,

00:06:30.010 --> 00:06:33.080
who is a mathematical
economist and also a

00:06:33.080 --> 00:06:34.330
practitioner.

00:06:38.520 --> 00:06:42.130
He's research director for
Ellington Capital.

00:06:42.130 --> 00:06:45.070
So, he's somewhat like me in
that he's interested both in

00:06:45.070 --> 00:06:48.340
theory and practice.

00:06:48.340 --> 00:06:55.650
But his course is definitely
more theoretical and

00:06:55.650 --> 00:06:57.510
mathematical than mine.

00:06:57.510 --> 00:07:02.240
His is entitled "Financial
Theory." And I can read some

00:07:02.240 --> 00:07:03.790
of the topics that --

00:07:03.790 --> 00:07:08.640
and his course also will appear
on Open Yale shortly.

00:07:08.640 --> 00:07:09.670
You can take the whole course.

00:07:09.670 --> 00:07:12.410
But I don't know -- it's
not up at this moment.

00:07:12.410 --> 00:07:15.640
It will be up in a
matter of months.

00:07:15.640 --> 00:07:18.100
So, I encourage you, if
you want to, to take

00:07:18.100 --> 00:07:21.390
Open Yale Econ 251.

00:07:21.390 --> 00:07:24.100
But the things that he talks
about in that course, if you

00:07:24.100 --> 00:07:27.080
read the topics in this course
you'll see that they're more

00:07:27.080 --> 00:07:29.560
mathematical and technical
than mine.

00:07:29.560 --> 00:07:33.330
He talks about ''Utilities,
Endowments and How It Leads to

00:07:33.330 --> 00:07:37.480
Equilibrium,'' ''Assets and
Time,'' ''The Mathematical

00:07:37.480 --> 00:07:41.680
Theory of Bond Pricing,''
''Dynamic Present Value,''

00:07:41.680 --> 00:07:44.650
''Social Security and the
Overlapping Generations

00:07:44.650 --> 00:07:48.430
Model,'' ''Uncertainty
and Hedging.''

00:07:48.430 --> 00:07:49.980
I'm quoting his titles.

00:07:49.980 --> 00:07:52.920
''State Pricing.'' That's kind
of an abstract theory.

00:07:52.920 --> 00:07:55.320
We talk about the price
of a state of nature.

00:07:55.320 --> 00:07:57.180
I won't explain that.

00:07:57.180 --> 00:08:01.190
He talks in some length about
the ''Theory of Risk'' and the

00:08:01.190 --> 00:08:03.880
''Capital Asset Pricing
Model,'' and about the

00:08:03.880 --> 00:08:08.710
''Leverage Cycle,'' which is
relevant to our crises.

00:08:08.710 --> 00:08:13.050
So, I recommend you take
Econ 251, but I don't

00:08:13.050 --> 00:08:15.300
expect you to take it.

00:08:15.300 --> 00:08:19.020
This course is self-contained.

00:08:19.020 --> 00:08:24.990
And I'm going to keep
mathematics to the minimum in

00:08:24.990 --> 00:08:26.760
these lectures.

00:08:26.760 --> 00:08:30.150
But the idea here is that we
can't avoid it completely.

00:08:30.150 --> 00:08:34.200
I personally am mathematically
inclined, too, but I'm

00:08:34.200 --> 00:08:37.220
understanding that we have
divided our subject matter.

00:08:37.220 --> 00:08:40.870
So, John Geanakoplos is doing
the math and the theory, and

00:08:40.870 --> 00:08:43.900
I'm doing the real world.

00:08:43.900 --> 00:08:45.780
It's not a complete division
like that, but it's

00:08:45.780 --> 00:08:47.970
something like that.

00:08:47.970 --> 00:08:50.310
So, I'm going to stay to that.

00:08:50.310 --> 00:08:55.760
I'm going to talk more about
institutions and history than

00:08:55.760 --> 00:08:57.010
about mathematics.

00:09:00.880 --> 00:09:04.210
Since I know that most of you
or many of you will not take

00:09:04.210 --> 00:09:07.910
Economics 251, what we are doing
is, I'll give a little

00:09:07.910 --> 00:09:13.400
indication of the mathematical
principles, more intuitive,

00:09:13.400 --> 00:09:19.880
and we have review sessions with
our teaching assistants.

00:09:19.880 --> 00:09:21.760
We plan to have six of those.

00:09:21.760 --> 00:09:25.910
And those will be on a
Friday in this room.

00:09:25.910 --> 00:09:28.890
And they won't be
on Open Yale.

00:09:28.890 --> 00:09:32.750
Those will cover the theory,
and it will be like a short

00:09:32.750 --> 00:09:35.790
form of Geanakoplos' course.

00:09:35.790 --> 00:09:37.700
And then we'll have
problem sets.

00:09:37.700 --> 00:09:39.770
And there will be six problems
sets, one for

00:09:39.770 --> 00:09:42.040
each of those sessions.

00:09:42.040 --> 00:09:46.380
So, there will be some
math in this course.

00:09:46.380 --> 00:09:52.600
I wanted to talk about the
purpose of this course, to

00:09:52.600 --> 00:09:54.520
clarify it.

00:09:54.520 --> 00:09:57.750
One thing is, what do I imagine
you're going to do

00:09:57.750 --> 00:09:59.210
with this course?

00:10:02.130 --> 00:10:06.650
Well, first of all, I pride
myself that I think I teach --

00:10:06.650 --> 00:10:08.660
if I might boast
for a minute --

00:10:08.660 --> 00:10:11.390
I think I teach one
of the most useful

00:10:11.390 --> 00:10:13.140
courses in Yale College.

00:10:13.140 --> 00:10:15.440
At least that's the way
I think about it.

00:10:15.440 --> 00:10:19.470
Because this course really
prepares you to do

00:10:19.470 --> 00:10:20.910
things in the world.

00:10:23.770 --> 00:10:27.360
By the way, I've been teaching
this course now for 25 years.

00:10:27.360 --> 00:10:30.570
I first taught it in
the fall of 1985.

00:10:30.570 --> 00:10:32.540
Now I don't know if that's
depressing or not.

00:10:32.540 --> 00:10:34.090
To me, it's great.

00:10:34.090 --> 00:10:36.650
I like to be able to
keep moving ahead.

00:10:36.650 --> 00:10:39.390
I wonder what my 1985
course looked like?

00:10:39.390 --> 00:10:42.600
Unfortunately, they didn't do
Open Yale and I can't go back

00:10:42.600 --> 00:10:44.220
and look at it.

00:10:44.220 --> 00:10:48.330
But I think I've gotten more
philosophical and maybe more

00:10:48.330 --> 00:10:51.690
real world oriented as
time has gone by.

00:10:51.690 --> 00:10:53.930
But the excitement I have
is when I go up --

00:10:53.930 --> 00:10:57.750
I give a lot of public talks,
and it's often on Wall Street.

00:10:57.750 --> 00:11:01.080
And when I do one on Wall
Street, I like to ask people

00:11:01.080 --> 00:11:02.630
for a show of hands.

00:11:02.630 --> 00:11:07.120
How many of you were in my
Economics 252 class?

00:11:07.120 --> 00:11:11.610
And I typically get one or two
at least who raise their hand.

00:11:11.610 --> 00:11:19.410
So, that's a source of pride to
me, that I was involved in

00:11:19.410 --> 00:11:21.920
the beginning of
their careers.

00:11:21.920 --> 00:11:24.820
And I hope I instilled some
kind of moral sense

00:11:24.820 --> 00:11:26.070
to what they do.

00:11:32.680 --> 00:11:35.970
But I should say I don't think
that most of you will go into

00:11:35.970 --> 00:11:40.140
finance, because I think
that most of

00:11:40.140 --> 00:11:42.580
you have other purposes.

00:11:42.580 --> 00:11:44.270
What does it mean to
go into finance?

00:11:44.270 --> 00:11:47.100
Well, it sounds like that means
you would be listed as

00:11:47.100 --> 00:11:53.600
someone who is very focused
on finance.

00:11:53.600 --> 00:12:00.580
But I think everyone should
know finance.

00:12:00.580 --> 00:12:03.930
This should be a required
course, actually, at Yale

00:12:03.930 --> 00:12:08.680
College, because finance is so
fundamental to what we do and

00:12:08.680 --> 00:12:12.500
the structure of our lives that
I don't see how you can

00:12:12.500 --> 00:12:15.410
avoid doing finance
if you want to do

00:12:15.410 --> 00:12:17.410
something big and important.

00:12:17.410 --> 00:12:19.570
Maybe you don't want to do that
either, so you might want

00:12:19.570 --> 00:12:22.510
to become a hermit and then
you don't need finance.

00:12:22.510 --> 00:12:29.850
But to me I like to think that
many of you have a sense of

00:12:29.850 --> 00:12:31.610
purpose in life.

00:12:31.610 --> 00:12:33.140
I should say --

00:12:33.140 --> 00:12:34.410
that sounded funny, didn't it?

00:12:34.410 --> 00:12:38.500
But what I'm saying is your
purpose is not to make money.

00:12:38.500 --> 00:12:41.560
And this is one thing about
finance that bothers me, is

00:12:41.560 --> 00:12:44.920
that people think that it's
a field for money-grubbing

00:12:44.920 --> 00:12:49.250
people who just want to
go out and make money.

00:12:49.250 --> 00:12:50.160
And I don't think so.

00:12:50.160 --> 00:12:55.060
I think it's a technology for
doing things, and you don't

00:12:55.060 --> 00:12:57.450
want to be mystified by it.

00:12:57.450 --> 00:13:00.310
When someone talks some
financial jargon, you don't

00:13:00.310 --> 00:13:03.830
want to say, I don't have a
clue what that's about,

00:13:03.830 --> 00:13:07.370
because what that's about is
how we make things happen.

00:13:07.370 --> 00:13:23.040
And so, I hope that you have
other purposes in life besides

00:13:23.040 --> 00:13:25.336
finance, even those of you
who go into finance.

00:13:28.020 --> 00:13:34.740
But the question is whether this
is a vocational course.

00:13:34.740 --> 00:13:39.360
Here at Yale College there has
been a long tradition that we

00:13:39.360 --> 00:13:41.700
are not a vocational school --

00:13:41.700 --> 00:13:43.580
I suppose you know that --

00:13:43.580 --> 00:13:46.390
that Yale is a liberal
arts [college]

00:13:46.390 --> 00:13:47.570
--

00:13:47.570 --> 00:13:50.730
we teach you the arts
and sciences.

00:13:50.730 --> 00:13:56.090
I actually went to look at the
charter and the act of the

00:13:56.090 --> 00:14:00.730
Connecticut government in 1701
that founded this university.

00:14:00.730 --> 00:14:05.430
This university was initially
mostly a training ground for

00:14:05.430 --> 00:14:07.010
the ministry.

00:14:07.010 --> 00:14:11.490
But I actually read in the
Acts of the Governor and

00:14:11.490 --> 00:14:15.440
Company of the Colony of
Connecticut: "Yale College is

00:14:15.440 --> 00:14:19.620
founded for the educating and
instructing of youth in good

00:14:19.620 --> 00:14:22.960
literature, arts, and sciences."
I think that is the

00:14:22.960 --> 00:14:25.480
motive here for this
university.

00:14:25.480 --> 00:14:31.270
And so, I think it is in some
level vocational, but it's not

00:14:31.270 --> 00:14:32.630
vulgar vocational.

00:14:32.630 --> 00:14:35.530
I want you to think about what
we're doing and how it fits

00:14:35.530 --> 00:14:37.300
into what you do
for your life.

00:14:42.790 --> 00:14:50.010
So, I think of finance as a kind
of engineering in a way.

00:14:50.010 --> 00:14:54.970
But it's an engineering that
works not with what we call a

00:14:54.970 --> 00:14:58.890
technical apparatus,
but with people.

00:14:58.890 --> 00:15:06.950
And so, if we want to understand
how to do these

00:15:06.950 --> 00:15:08.970
things, we have to get
some technical

00:15:08.970 --> 00:15:10.840
apparatus under our belt.

00:15:10.840 --> 00:15:14.840
And that's what I'm going to
try to do in this course.

00:15:14.840 --> 00:15:20.830
The textbook that I chose for
this course is by Frank

00:15:20.830 --> 00:15:23.910
Fabozzi, who is a professor
at the Yale School

00:15:23.910 --> 00:15:24.700
of Management --

00:15:24.700 --> 00:15:27.260
well, with two co-authors.

00:15:27.260 --> 00:15:32.920
We have Franco Modigliani, for
whom I have some personal

00:15:32.920 --> 00:15:38.850
affection, because he was my
dissertation adviser at MIT,

00:15:38.850 --> 00:15:47.390
and who unfortunately died in
2003, and Frank Jones of

00:15:47.390 --> 00:15:48.890
Guardian Life Insurance
Company.

00:15:55.890 --> 00:15:58.300
I've also written joint
papers with, well, two

00:15:58.300 --> 00:15:59.140
of the three authors.

00:15:59.140 --> 00:16:03.230
I've written joint papers with
Fabozzi and with Modigliani --

00:16:03.230 --> 00:16:04.590
research papers.

00:16:04.590 --> 00:16:09.170
But they're similar to
me in many ways.

00:16:09.170 --> 00:16:12.800
They're interested
in the details.

00:16:12.800 --> 00:16:15.860
I hope you get interested
in the details.

00:16:15.860 --> 00:16:19.790
I find this textbook
fascinating for me.

00:16:19.790 --> 00:16:24.580
Well, I first read this
book when I first

00:16:24.580 --> 00:16:26.080
started assigning it.

00:16:26.080 --> 00:16:30.770
I was going on vacation with
my friend Jeremy Siegel and

00:16:30.770 --> 00:16:33.210
our families, who's a professor
at the Wharton

00:16:33.210 --> 00:16:39.444
School, and I brought this book
as my poolside reading.

00:16:39.444 --> 00:16:42.160
And I was sitting there
with this book.

00:16:42.160 --> 00:16:46.840
Other people were reading
novels and fun things.

00:16:46.840 --> 00:16:49.350
I don't know what they thought
of me reading this textbook by

00:16:49.350 --> 00:16:54.890
the pool, but I thought this is
great, because I thought I

00:16:54.890 --> 00:16:57.570
knew most of what's in here,
but there's a lot of things

00:16:57.570 --> 00:16:59.850
that I still didn't know
and it was answering

00:16:59.850 --> 00:17:01.170
all kinds of questions.

00:17:01.170 --> 00:17:04.810
Things you always wanted to
know about real estate

00:17:04.810 --> 00:17:07.710
securities, OK, but you
never found out.

00:17:07.710 --> 00:17:09.400
Well it's all answered here.

00:17:09.400 --> 00:17:11.680
So, I hope you can
take that spirit

00:17:11.680 --> 00:17:15.250
in reading the textbook.

00:17:15.250 --> 00:17:19.770
That's the only book you have
to purchase for this course.

00:17:19.770 --> 00:17:29.550
And it's the main work
that you have.

00:17:29.550 --> 00:17:35.320
So, I'm going to ask you about
the details on exams. The

00:17:35.320 --> 00:17:39.190
kinds of municipal securities
we have and how the rating

00:17:39.190 --> 00:17:41.890
agencies rate them, that's
part of this course.

00:17:41.890 --> 00:17:45.830
I believe the details matter.

00:17:45.830 --> 00:17:47.550
And so, I'm not going to
just ask you broad

00:17:47.550 --> 00:17:48.890
generalities on the exam.

00:17:48.890 --> 00:17:52.560
I'm going to ask you
the details.

00:17:52.560 --> 00:17:55.680
It's a little bit like teaching
a language, right?

00:17:55.680 --> 00:17:59.280
Learning a language is really
important, and you've got to

00:17:59.280 --> 00:18:00.340
learn all the words, right?

00:18:00.340 --> 00:18:02.100
There's thousands of them.

00:18:02.100 --> 00:18:02.820
It's like that.

00:18:02.820 --> 00:18:04.645
You're going to be learning
the words of finance.

00:18:08.510 --> 00:18:15.060
So, I have another book also,
which is actually not done

00:18:15.060 --> 00:18:20.470
yet, but you can access it
through Classes*v2, and later

00:18:20.470 --> 00:18:22.970
it will come out as
a published book.

00:18:22.970 --> 00:18:26.510
But I'm working on
a book called --

00:18:26.510 --> 00:18:28.810
well, I don't know what it
will be called finally.

00:18:28.810 --> 00:18:30.570
When you're writing a book,
one thing you learn as an

00:18:30.570 --> 00:18:33.370
author is, you can never be
sure what the title of the

00:18:33.370 --> 00:18:34.520
book will be.

00:18:34.520 --> 00:18:37.540
Because if somebody else uses
the same title and you're

00:18:37.540 --> 00:18:40.960
done, somebody else gets to it
first, you've got to change

00:18:40.960 --> 00:18:42.030
your title.

00:18:42.030 --> 00:18:46.600
But at this moment the title of
my book is "Finance and the

00:18:46.600 --> 00:18:51.200
Good Society." I'm not sure
when it will be out.

00:18:51.200 --> 00:18:54.220
I was hoping next year, but now
I'm thinking it might take

00:18:54.220 --> 00:18:55.890
longer than that.

00:18:55.890 --> 00:18:58.440
So, you have something
that's imperfect.

00:18:58.440 --> 00:19:03.090
I hope you excuse me when
you look at the

00:19:03.090 --> 00:19:04.590
chapters of this book.

00:19:04.590 --> 00:19:06.890
You don't have quite all
the chapters either.

00:19:06.890 --> 00:19:09.960
But I just thought it was a
good thing to put it in

00:19:09.960 --> 00:19:12.710
process for you to --

00:19:12.710 --> 00:19:17.050
maybe if you have ideas you can
tell me and the book will

00:19:17.050 --> 00:19:19.870
change with your input.

00:19:19.870 --> 00:19:22.230
To me it's a good way to write
a book, is to be writing a

00:19:22.230 --> 00:19:24.420
book and teaching a
class at the same

00:19:24.420 --> 00:19:26.330
time on the same topic.

00:19:26.330 --> 00:19:27.420
It's more social.

00:19:27.420 --> 00:19:30.220
You know, you just sit in your
office and write and you end

00:19:30.220 --> 00:19:33.280
up feeling sterile.

00:19:33.280 --> 00:19:35.760
So, this makes it more
alive to me to do

00:19:35.760 --> 00:19:36.890
that at the same time.

00:19:36.890 --> 00:19:39.520
But I'll tell you what
my book is about.

00:19:39.520 --> 00:19:41.950
The title that I now have,
"Finance and the Good

00:19:41.950 --> 00:19:46.670
Society," may sound to some
people like an oxymoron,

00:19:46.670 --> 00:19:49.230
because they're kind
of incompatible.

00:19:49.230 --> 00:19:52.530
People are angry about
finance these days.

00:19:52.530 --> 00:19:53.360
We've had --

00:19:53.360 --> 00:19:54.880
and this is going to be
an important part

00:19:54.880 --> 00:19:55.960
of this course --

00:19:55.960 --> 00:19:59.930
we've had the worst financial
crisis since the Great

00:19:59.930 --> 00:20:02.050
Depression of the 1930s.

00:20:02.050 --> 00:20:05.950
And it's been a worldwide
financial crisis and it isn't

00:20:05.950 --> 00:20:09.010
over yet, or it's not clear
that it's over yet.

00:20:09.010 --> 00:20:11.140
And people are angry.

00:20:11.140 --> 00:20:15.480
People are angry about finance,
people who seem to be

00:20:15.480 --> 00:20:19.720
getting rich often it seems
at the expense of others.

00:20:19.720 --> 00:20:22.610
Or they seem to be lobbying
their governments to give them

00:20:22.610 --> 00:20:25.720
breaks and bailouts,
and they walk home

00:20:25.720 --> 00:20:27.860
with billions of dollars.

00:20:27.860 --> 00:20:32.160
Something seems immoral
and wrong.

00:20:32.160 --> 00:20:35.960
Well, I'm sure some immoral
things are happening, but I

00:20:35.960 --> 00:20:39.330
don't think that finance
as a whole is wrong.

00:20:39.330 --> 00:20:42.660
And I think of it as
a noble profession.

00:20:42.660 --> 00:20:47.810
So, I wanted to try to put
it in perspective.

00:20:47.810 --> 00:20:51.450
And it's especially important
when talking to young people

00:20:51.450 --> 00:20:54.460
like yourselves, because you're
launching out on a

00:20:54.460 --> 00:20:59.950
career, and I want that to be a
moral and purposeful career.

00:20:59.950 --> 00:21:04.700
And I want to put finance
in the perspective.

00:21:04.700 --> 00:21:09.790
So, the theme that I want
to develop in my book

00:21:09.790 --> 00:21:12.620
is that part --

00:21:12.620 --> 00:21:16.140
you know, we live in a
capitalist world now and this

00:21:16.140 --> 00:21:22.220
world is increasingly
built on finance.

00:21:22.220 --> 00:21:25.140
Some people call it we're living
in the era of financial

00:21:25.140 --> 00:21:26.450
capitalism.

00:21:26.450 --> 00:21:30.080
We have these big multinational
institutions

00:21:30.080 --> 00:21:33.120
that are owned by huge numbers,
maybe millions, of

00:21:33.120 --> 00:21:36.030
shareholders dispersed
all over the world.

00:21:36.030 --> 00:21:38.970
And what makes the whole
thing work and click?

00:21:38.970 --> 00:21:41.105
It's the financial
arrangements.

00:21:44.360 --> 00:21:48.240
The world is discovering the
importance of finance.

00:21:48.240 --> 00:21:51.440
When I go to a foreign country
and give a talk, I

00:21:51.440 --> 00:21:53.780
find that people --

00:21:53.780 --> 00:21:55.840
it doesn't matter what country
-- they're generally very

00:21:55.840 --> 00:21:59.390
interested in finance, because
they think that our modern

00:21:59.390 --> 00:22:03.290
financial techniques are part
of what's making so many

00:22:03.290 --> 00:22:07.140
places in the world grow
at rapid rates now.

00:22:07.140 --> 00:22:11.470
We're living in a time in
history when the developing

00:22:11.470 --> 00:22:14.980
world is exploding with growth,
and these countries

00:22:14.980 --> 00:22:17.890
that are doing that are
countries that are adopting

00:22:17.890 --> 00:22:19.560
modern finance.

00:22:19.560 --> 00:22:23.340
So, I want this to go right,
and I want this to be

00:22:23.340 --> 00:22:24.620
developing a good society.

00:22:27.780 --> 00:22:31.990
By good society, I mean a just
and fair society that allows

00:22:31.990 --> 00:22:37.130
people to develop their
talents and expertise.

00:22:37.130 --> 00:22:50.300
So, another thought I had was
that the field of finance--

00:22:50.300 --> 00:22:51.550
let me give you another slide.

00:22:55.420 --> 00:22:59.640
I said I view this course as
one of the most important

00:22:59.640 --> 00:23:02.950
courses in Yale College, at
least from a standpoint of

00:23:02.950 --> 00:23:05.460
your lives and careers.

00:23:05.460 --> 00:23:09.550
I wanted to compare finance
jobs with jobs.

00:23:09.550 --> 00:23:11.560
And I don't mean to put down
other departments, but at

00:23:11.560 --> 00:23:14.700
least vocationally, let's
put this in perspective.

00:23:14.700 --> 00:23:17.580
I wanted to compare jobs
in finance with

00:23:17.580 --> 00:23:19.770
jobs in other fields.

00:23:19.770 --> 00:23:24.770
So, this is a chart that I
constructed using data from

00:23:24.770 --> 00:23:26.720
the Bureau of Labor
Statistics.

00:23:26.720 --> 00:23:30.490
And what it has is the number
of people in various

00:23:30.490 --> 00:23:34.770
occupations in 2008 and
their projections

00:23:34.770 --> 00:23:37.540
for the same in 2018.

00:23:37.540 --> 00:23:41.860
So, the red bar is for 2018,
and we'll emphasize that,

00:23:41.860 --> 00:23:43.340
because you'll be just
getting into your

00:23:43.340 --> 00:23:46.290
careers when that comes.

00:23:46.290 --> 00:23:50.230
So, it says, if you look at
financial analysts in the

00:23:50.230 --> 00:23:53.760
United States there's
almost 300,000.

00:23:53.760 --> 00:23:57.340
Financial managers, it's
over half a million.

00:23:57.340 --> 00:23:59.490
Personal financial advisers,
a quarter of a

00:23:59.490 --> 00:24:01.820
million, all right?

00:24:01.820 --> 00:24:05.000
These are people who specialize
entirely in one

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:06.990
form of finance or another.

00:24:06.990 --> 00:24:08.680
But compare that with
economists.

00:24:08.680 --> 00:24:10.720
Look at that.

00:24:10.720 --> 00:24:11.080
What is that?

00:24:11.080 --> 00:24:12.910
About 20,000?

00:24:12.910 --> 00:24:14.600
I think they're excluding
professors.

00:24:14.600 --> 00:24:16.700
But, you know, just economists
out there --

00:24:16.700 --> 00:24:18.180
not very many.

00:24:18.180 --> 00:24:19.870
How about astronomers?

00:24:19.870 --> 00:24:20.290
OK.

00:24:20.290 --> 00:24:23.010
I can't even read that.

00:24:23.010 --> 00:24:26.700
I love astronomy by the way, but
I think I made the right

00:24:26.700 --> 00:24:27.880
choice when I decided --

00:24:27.880 --> 00:24:29.790
well, I shouldn't say that,
you never know.

00:24:29.790 --> 00:24:31.610
We all have to do something
different.

00:24:31.610 --> 00:24:36.170
And you could become an
astronomer, but there aren't

00:24:36.170 --> 00:24:39.650
many jobs in astronomy.

00:24:39.650 --> 00:24:43.090
Sociologists, political
scientists, just not many

00:24:43.090 --> 00:24:45.390
compared to -- this is just
enormously bigger.

00:24:45.390 --> 00:24:46.930
Or mathematicians.

00:24:46.930 --> 00:24:50.150
I also put one oddball
field on here:

00:24:50.150 --> 00:24:52.650
massage therapists, OK?

00:24:52.650 --> 00:24:57.130
The number of massage therapist
jobs outnumbers any

00:24:57.130 --> 00:25:01.600
of those other fields by,
what is it, 100:1.

00:25:01.600 --> 00:25:03.790
So, this is the kind of

00:25:03.790 --> 00:25:05.810
disappointment that people face.

00:25:05.810 --> 00:25:08.260
You go to the college
or university --

00:25:08.260 --> 00:25:10.760
this is very much on my mind
-- you go to the university

00:25:10.760 --> 00:25:13.340
and you develop special skills,
and you leave and then

00:25:13.340 --> 00:25:16.690
you end up driving a taxi.

00:25:16.690 --> 00:25:19.210
That doesn't mean that I want
to become vocational.

00:25:19.210 --> 00:25:21.950
I mean, I don't want to just
train you for a job, but I

00:25:21.950 --> 00:25:23.140
want to be relevant.

00:25:23.140 --> 00:25:27.080
And it seems to me that
I can be relevant in

00:25:27.080 --> 00:25:29.080
talking about finance.

00:25:29.080 --> 00:25:39.090
And so, that's the basic core
that I wanted to get.

00:25:53.570 --> 00:25:56.130
I mentioned before that people
think that finance is the

00:25:56.130 --> 00:25:58.930
field for people who want to get
rich, who want to make a

00:25:58.930 --> 00:26:02.050
lot of money.

00:26:02.050 --> 00:26:05.575
Well, I think that's
right, actually.

00:26:05.575 --> 00:26:07.550
[LAUGHTER]

00:26:07.550 --> 00:26:11.660
I don't advise you to
take that as your --

00:26:11.660 --> 00:26:14.600
but I wanted to talk about
that a little bit.

00:26:14.600 --> 00:26:19.800
So, one thing that you'll note,
Forbes Magazine has an

00:26:19.800 --> 00:26:23.625
annual list of the 400 richest
people in America.

00:26:26.230 --> 00:26:30.980
So, I looked at that list. Who
do you think they are?

00:26:30.980 --> 00:26:34.920
Most of you probably have not
read this list. You might

00:26:34.920 --> 00:26:37.650
think that, well, who makes
a lot of money?

00:26:37.650 --> 00:26:38.920
Well, it's athletes.

00:26:38.920 --> 00:26:42.270
Football players, right?

00:26:42.270 --> 00:26:45.310
Baseball players.

00:26:45.310 --> 00:26:45.740
And who else?

00:26:45.740 --> 00:26:48.020
Oh, movie stars, right?

00:26:48.020 --> 00:26:49.830
They make a lot of money.

00:26:49.830 --> 00:26:53.940
So, how many do you think of
those are on the Forbes 400 of

00:26:53.940 --> 00:26:57.080
the richest people in America?

00:26:57.080 --> 00:27:01.080
Well, as I read the list I
didn't see a single movie star

00:27:01.080 --> 00:27:02.990
or a single athlete.

00:27:02.990 --> 00:27:04.840
There is -- it depends
on how you define it.

00:27:04.840 --> 00:27:08.040
Oprah Winfrey is on
the list. OK?

00:27:08.040 --> 00:27:09.950
You've heard of her.

00:27:09.950 --> 00:27:14.080
She's in the entertainment
business.

00:27:14.080 --> 00:27:17.100
But you know, she's also
a finance person.

00:27:17.100 --> 00:27:20.020
She runs big businesses.

00:27:20.020 --> 00:27:23.410
She's into making
things happen.

00:27:23.410 --> 00:27:27.040
And I can assure you that she
knows finance, at least some

00:27:27.040 --> 00:27:30.020
basic finance.

00:27:30.020 --> 00:27:33.270
You see, finance gets you
to build organizations.

00:27:33.270 --> 00:27:34.570
That's how it's done.

00:27:34.570 --> 00:27:37.160
And it means raising capital
to make things

00:27:37.160 --> 00:27:39.190
happen on a big scale.

00:27:39.190 --> 00:27:43.060
You know, no athlete is as
powerful as one of these

00:27:43.060 --> 00:27:47.900
random guys on the
Forbes 400 list.

00:27:47.900 --> 00:27:48.580
It's interesting.

00:27:48.580 --> 00:27:52.070
I looked down the list and I
didn't spot a single Nobel

00:27:52.070 --> 00:27:54.600
Prize winner.

00:27:54.600 --> 00:27:55.980
Maybe I missed one.

00:27:55.980 --> 00:27:58.080
I looked for best
selling authors.

00:27:58.080 --> 00:28:01.280
I found one: Bill Gates,
who wrote a book

00:28:01.280 --> 00:28:04.640
called The Road Ahead.

00:28:04.640 --> 00:28:08.540
But there are not many best
selling authors either.

00:28:08.540 --> 00:28:10.280
What do they have in common?

00:28:10.280 --> 00:28:12.550
Now about a third of them just
inherited it from their

00:28:12.550 --> 00:28:16.390
parents, but most of them
did it themselves.

00:28:16.390 --> 00:28:19.900
They just made huge
sums of money.

00:28:19.900 --> 00:28:22.560
And what do they do?

00:28:22.560 --> 00:28:26.370
Well, they're typically in some
boring line of business.

00:28:26.370 --> 00:28:28.870
They make something,
but they're doing

00:28:28.870 --> 00:28:30.650
it on a vast scale.

00:28:30.650 --> 00:28:33.930
And so, that means they're
making deals, they're putting

00:28:33.930 --> 00:28:36.180
things together, they're buying
companies, they're

00:28:36.180 --> 00:28:39.760
absorbing other companies
into their's.

00:28:39.760 --> 00:28:42.990
There's something powerful about
an ability to do that.

00:28:42.990 --> 00:28:47.590
And I think that it's good
for you to understand and

00:28:47.590 --> 00:28:48.873
appreciate that.

00:28:54.140 --> 00:28:57.500
By the way, Forbes has another
list called the Forbes

00:28:57.500 --> 00:29:00.130
Celebrity 100.

00:29:00.130 --> 00:29:03.050
And to be on that list, you
have to be a celebrity.

00:29:03.050 --> 00:29:05.780
It's a completely different
list. Oprah is on both lists,

00:29:05.780 --> 00:29:09.380
but she's practically
the only one.

00:29:09.380 --> 00:29:12.400
Steven Spielberg is on
both lists, I think.

00:29:12.400 --> 00:29:16.970
He makes movies, but he has
a whole company called

00:29:16.970 --> 00:29:20.480
DreamWorks, and he finances all
kinds of movies, so he's a

00:29:20.480 --> 00:29:23.210
businessperson as well.

00:29:23.210 --> 00:29:26.300
So, I don't think of finance
as a mathematical --

00:29:26.300 --> 00:29:29.420
I mean it is mathematical, it
has a core element of that.

00:29:29.420 --> 00:29:32.840
But to me it's about making
things happen and about

00:29:32.840 --> 00:29:37.450
putting together deals and
getting people incentivized to

00:29:37.450 --> 00:29:41.080
do something, and getting
capital, getting resources in

00:29:41.080 --> 00:29:45.550
a massive scale so that
something can happen.

00:29:45.550 --> 00:29:50.160
And so, that's what this
course is about.

00:29:50.160 --> 00:29:54.086
Oh, Jerry Seinfeld is listed by
Forbes as a possibility --

00:29:57.800 --> 00:29:59.330
he's about the only one --

00:29:59.330 --> 00:30:02.650
to make the list of
the Forbes 400.

00:30:02.650 --> 00:30:05.630
But he isn't there yet.

00:30:05.630 --> 00:30:13.690
I don't mean to diminish these
celebrity people, but there's

00:30:13.690 --> 00:30:16.690
something else that goes on in
finance, and it's quiet.

00:30:16.690 --> 00:30:19.090
It's behind the -- actually,
most of the Forbes 400 you've

00:30:19.090 --> 00:30:20.240
never heard of.

00:30:20.240 --> 00:30:23.130
They're kind of behind the
scenes doing things that are

00:30:23.130 --> 00:30:28.070
big and important, but they
don't get on the news so much.

00:30:28.070 --> 00:30:29.220
It's one of the ironies
of life.

00:30:29.220 --> 00:30:32.360
You might aspire to do this,
to get on the Forbes 400.

00:30:32.360 --> 00:30:36.940
You can do it and still nobody
knows who you are or cares.

00:30:36.940 --> 00:30:40.270
So that's just as well, I
think, for many people.

00:30:40.270 --> 00:30:42.720
So then, the question is:
Suppose you get on the Forbes

00:30:42.720 --> 00:30:45.690
400, what are you going
to do with it?

00:30:45.690 --> 00:30:48.130
In other words, to get on the
Forbes 400 you have to have

00:30:48.130 --> 00:30:50.110
made at least a billion
dollars.

00:30:50.110 --> 00:30:53.740
So that means, you have in your
own portfolio a thousand

00:30:53.740 --> 00:30:55.410
million dollars.

00:30:55.410 --> 00:30:58.250
That's the minimum to make the
list. So, what are you going

00:30:58.250 --> 00:30:59.770
to do with a thousand million?

00:30:59.770 --> 00:31:02.920
Any ideas what would
you do with it?

00:31:02.920 --> 00:31:05.580
You could buy cars, right?

00:31:05.580 --> 00:31:09.940
How many sports cars could
you buy for that?

00:31:12.930 --> 00:31:13.500
What could you do?

00:31:13.500 --> 00:31:15.170
You could buy 20 houses.

00:31:15.170 --> 00:31:17.210
But that doesn't begin
-- you could buy 20

00:31:17.210 --> 00:31:18.360
houses and so what?

00:31:18.360 --> 00:31:21.780
You know, you still have
900 million leftover.

00:31:21.780 --> 00:31:25.130
So, what are you going to
do with all that money?

00:31:25.130 --> 00:31:29.020
And that's a question.

00:31:29.020 --> 00:31:33.920
Now, some people who do that,
who make all this money, try

00:31:33.920 --> 00:31:39.660
to see if they can maximize
their appearance of wealth.

00:31:39.660 --> 00:31:44.370
They try to show to the world
how rich they are.

00:31:44.370 --> 00:31:47.610
So, you just build the biggest
mansion and you do something

00:31:47.610 --> 00:31:48.910
really spectacular.

00:31:48.910 --> 00:31:51.920
But when you got a billion
dollars, there isn't a house

00:31:51.920 --> 00:31:56.160
in the country you could buy
for a billion dollars.

00:31:56.160 --> 00:31:58.220
You can only stay in one
at a time, right?

00:31:58.220 --> 00:32:01.150
So, what are you going to do?

00:32:01.150 --> 00:32:04.220
But there are people who do
that, and I think that there's

00:32:04.220 --> 00:32:09.230
a history of disgust for those
people, a long history.

00:32:09.230 --> 00:32:13.370
We don't like people
who do that.

00:32:13.370 --> 00:32:15.550
It's almost like it's
a big mistake.

00:32:15.550 --> 00:32:18.260
Why would you do that when
people don't like people who

00:32:18.260 --> 00:32:21.390
show off their wealth?

00:32:21.390 --> 00:32:24.030
There's evidence that people
feel that way in many

00:32:24.030 --> 00:32:26.920
different countries and
cultures, because lots of

00:32:26.920 --> 00:32:30.870
countries in history have what
are called sumptuary laws.

00:32:30.870 --> 00:32:35.240
It goes back at least to 700 BC
in Ancient Greece with the

00:32:35.240 --> 00:32:36.890
Locrian code.

00:32:36.890 --> 00:32:39.840
These are laws prohibiting
people from conspicuous

00:32:39.840 --> 00:32:40.950
consumption.

00:32:40.950 --> 00:32:43.240
And they've been in so many
different countries that I

00:32:43.240 --> 00:32:49.150
think it's evidence that
something is amiss with making

00:32:49.150 --> 00:32:54.930
wealth as the objective
of your life.

00:32:58.170 --> 00:33:01.820
So, one of the themes in
the beginning of our

00:33:01.820 --> 00:33:03.660
reading list is --

00:33:03.660 --> 00:33:10.440
I think there's a movement afoot
today around the world

00:33:10.440 --> 00:33:13.360
of thinking about this problem,
that you can get so

00:33:13.360 --> 00:33:18.690
big and powerful if you build
a business and you use the

00:33:18.690 --> 00:33:25.000
financial techniques that are
successful for other people,

00:33:25.000 --> 00:33:31.460
but it's meaningless unless
you give it away.

00:33:31.460 --> 00:33:35.680
And so, what else can you do
with all this wealth but plan

00:33:35.680 --> 00:33:36.930
to give it away.

00:33:39.410 --> 00:33:41.470
So, one thing I have on the
reading list right at the

00:33:41.470 --> 00:33:45.910
beginning is a chapter from a
book -- well, the title of the

00:33:45.910 --> 00:33:50.560
book is The Gospel of Wealth
and Other Essays and it was

00:33:50.560 --> 00:33:52.910
written by Andrew Carnegie.

00:33:52.910 --> 00:33:57.290
Actually, he wrote a short
article in a magazine called

00:33:57.290 --> 00:33:59.100
"Wealth" in 1889.

00:33:59.100 --> 00:34:02.560
And in the final paragraph he
used the term "gospel of

00:34:02.560 --> 00:34:10.010
wealth" and it was picked up
all over the world as just

00:34:10.010 --> 00:34:11.390
outrageous.

00:34:11.390 --> 00:34:14.390
And so, it became named
The Gospel of Wealth.

00:34:14.390 --> 00:34:16.770
So, later in the early 20th
century he came out with a

00:34:16.770 --> 00:34:19.450
book entitled The Gospel
of Wealth.

00:34:19.450 --> 00:34:21.330
And that's what I
have assigned.

00:34:21.330 --> 00:34:24.590
You can click on it on the
reading list. And Andrew

00:34:24.590 --> 00:34:26.780
Carnegie was one of these --

00:34:26.780 --> 00:34:29.530
they didn't have Forbes 400, but
he was one of the richest

00:34:29.530 --> 00:34:35.690
men in America through his
Carnegie Steel Company, very

00:34:35.690 --> 00:34:37.770
much steeped in finance.

00:34:37.770 --> 00:34:42.590
But he decided when he wrote
his essay, The Gospel of

00:34:42.590 --> 00:34:50.360
Wealth, in 1889 that once a
person reaches middle age,

00:34:50.360 --> 00:34:55.120
like 50 or 55, and has made a
lot of money, they really have

00:34:55.120 --> 00:34:57.550
to go into philanthropy.

00:34:57.550 --> 00:34:59.270
There's a moral imperative.

00:34:59.270 --> 00:35:03.520
So, the theme of The Gospel of
Wealth was some people are

00:35:03.520 --> 00:35:07.360
just better at what he called
affairs than other people.

00:35:07.360 --> 00:35:08.460
That means business.

00:35:08.460 --> 00:35:11.780
Some people have a sense of
how to make things happen.

00:35:11.780 --> 00:35:15.310
These people have a moral
obligation to make this work

00:35:15.310 --> 00:35:18.550
for the benefit of humankind.

00:35:18.550 --> 00:35:25.690
And that means, while they're
still young, they have to take

00:35:25.690 --> 00:35:29.980
their fortune and give it all
away before they die.

00:35:29.980 --> 00:35:33.200
Because if they don't give it
all away, it's nonsense.

00:35:33.200 --> 00:35:36.390
If you make a billion dollars
and you leave it to your

00:35:36.390 --> 00:35:40.310
children, chances are they're
not like you.

00:35:40.310 --> 00:35:43.295
They're not going to be
interested in working hard and

00:35:43.295 --> 00:35:45.000
making things happen.

00:35:45.000 --> 00:35:46.880
They're just going
to squander it.

00:35:46.880 --> 00:35:51.360
And so, that's what the
moral obligation is.

00:35:51.360 --> 00:35:54.890
You have to stop at age,
let's say 55 --

00:35:54.890 --> 00:35:56.850
OK, you still got time left --

00:35:56.850 --> 00:35:58.900
and then use your
same talents.

00:35:58.900 --> 00:36:01.760
So, it was almost a theory of
capitalism -- it is a theory

00:36:01.760 --> 00:36:02.800
of capitalism.

00:36:02.800 --> 00:36:07.370
It is a theory that some people
are just more practical

00:36:07.370 --> 00:36:11.370
and hardworking and
business-oriented, and these

00:36:11.370 --> 00:36:16.060
people can find things to do
that benefit mankind, and they

00:36:16.060 --> 00:36:17.040
should do it.

00:36:17.040 --> 00:36:19.650
So, there's a natural
selection.

00:36:19.650 --> 00:36:20.410
This is Carnegie.

00:36:20.410 --> 00:36:22.490
I'm not endorsing
this entirely.

00:36:22.490 --> 00:36:25.470
I think there's an element of
truth to The Gospel of Wealth,

00:36:25.470 --> 00:36:31.060
but it's not exactly true.

00:36:31.060 --> 00:36:33.310
But the element of truth is
right, that people like

00:36:33.310 --> 00:36:35.660
Carnegie who was a very
gifted person -- you

00:36:35.660 --> 00:36:36.240
know what he did?

00:36:36.240 --> 00:36:39.420
He set up the Carnegie Institute
of Technology, now

00:36:39.420 --> 00:36:41.850
called Carnegie Mellon
University.

00:36:41.850 --> 00:36:46.370
He set up the Carnegie Endowment
for World Peace,

00:36:46.370 --> 00:36:48.880
Carnegie Hall in New York.

00:36:48.880 --> 00:36:50.210
He probably gave something
to Yale, too.

00:36:50.210 --> 00:36:51.180
Anyone know?

00:36:51.180 --> 00:36:52.540
Is there a Carnegie?

00:36:52.540 --> 00:36:54.900
He gave to like every imaginable
university.

00:36:54.900 --> 00:36:58.870
I know at Princeton they
have a Lake Carnegie.

00:36:58.870 --> 00:37:03.290
He was visiting Princeton and
someone pointed out this kind

00:37:03.290 --> 00:37:08.030
of swampy land and said we'd
like to really create a lake.

00:37:08.030 --> 00:37:09.800
So, he said, fine.

00:37:09.800 --> 00:37:12.080
He gave them money to create
Lake Carnegie.

00:37:12.080 --> 00:37:17.240
And he also gave the money for
the prize for the first true

00:37:17.240 --> 00:37:19.280
competition on Lake Carnegie.

00:37:19.280 --> 00:37:22.620
So, he just had all kinds
of gifts he gave away.

00:37:26.150 --> 00:37:27.330
I also have -- it's
interesting, I

00:37:27.330 --> 00:37:29.280
found this on the web.

00:37:29.280 --> 00:37:33.300
Thomas Edison, the inventor,
was so impressed with

00:37:33.300 --> 00:37:36.680
Carnegie's The Gospel of
Wealth that Edison was

00:37:36.680 --> 00:37:42.290
developing the sound movie, I
think it was 1914, but he

00:37:42.290 --> 00:37:43.450
didn't perfect it.

00:37:43.450 --> 00:37:46.550
But he said the first sound
movie should involve geniuses

00:37:46.550 --> 00:37:47.590
of our time.

00:37:47.590 --> 00:37:52.270
So, he made a sound movie of
Carnegie reading from his The

00:37:52.270 --> 00:37:53.440
Gospel of Wealth.

00:37:53.440 --> 00:37:57.210
Unfortunately, the visual side
of it somehow got lost. Maybe

00:37:57.210 --> 00:37:58.610
it didn't work.

00:37:58.610 --> 00:38:01.300
We only have the soundtrack
from the movie.

00:38:01.300 --> 00:38:05.290
So, you can listen to Carnegie
reading from this book in

00:38:05.290 --> 00:38:10.270
1914, and it's the only
recording of Carnegie's voice

00:38:10.270 --> 00:38:11.520
that survived.

00:38:13.710 --> 00:38:17.520
Since then, Bill Gates and
Warren Buffett and others of

00:38:17.520 --> 00:38:25.540
the Forbes 400 have done a
campaign to get billionaires

00:38:25.540 --> 00:38:28.130
around the world to commit to
give most of their wealth

00:38:28.130 --> 00:38:31.230
away, while they're
still alive.

00:38:31.230 --> 00:38:35.940
And I'm trying to get one of
these people to speak to our

00:38:35.940 --> 00:38:38.290
class, but I haven't
yet arranged that.

00:38:43.210 --> 00:38:48.570
I also have on the website a
review from 1890 of Carnegie's

00:38:48.570 --> 00:38:53.350
original essay from a California
newspaper, and they

00:38:53.350 --> 00:38:56.090
were so negative about it.

00:38:56.090 --> 00:38:59.600
They said, Carnegie thinks that
making wealth and giving

00:38:59.600 --> 00:39:04.270
it away is a noble cause.

00:39:04.270 --> 00:39:06.590
That cannot possibly be right.

00:39:06.590 --> 00:39:10.290
These people who make money are
not the most enlightened

00:39:10.290 --> 00:39:13.640
and smart people in our world.

00:39:13.640 --> 00:39:15.780
I think that the truth lies
somewhere in between.

00:39:15.780 --> 00:39:19.740
But we do have a society
now where people --

00:39:19.740 --> 00:39:25.440
we have an increasing
concentration of wealth at the

00:39:25.440 --> 00:39:28.620
top, and I don't know what we're
going to do about this.

00:39:28.620 --> 00:39:33.210
This is a trend that
may continue.

00:39:33.210 --> 00:39:35.080
And so, this is the thing
I want to think

00:39:35.080 --> 00:39:36.050
about in this course.

00:39:36.050 --> 00:39:38.580
I don't think finance
necessarily does this.

00:39:38.580 --> 00:39:41.860
It may be a bubble, that there
is currently a bubble in

00:39:41.860 --> 00:39:46.420
financial careers and that you
are going to be disappointed,

00:39:46.420 --> 00:39:50.310
because 20 or 30 years from
now if you go into a

00:39:50.310 --> 00:39:55.210
finance-related field, you'll
find that it's not as

00:39:55.210 --> 00:39:58.430
lucrative as you hoped.

00:39:58.430 --> 00:40:00.130
That kind of happens, right?

00:40:00.130 --> 00:40:03.730
When a field becomes known for
having a lot of successful

00:40:03.730 --> 00:40:05.640
people, then more young
people go into it and

00:40:05.640 --> 00:40:07.720
they swamp the field.

00:40:07.720 --> 00:40:10.570
On the other hand, I think that
it will always be true

00:40:10.570 --> 00:40:14.280
that just because of the power
of the technology the top

00:40:14.280 --> 00:40:18.420
wealthiest people in the world
will be finance-related.

00:40:18.420 --> 00:40:22.710
And I think that they will have
a moral obligation to

00:40:22.710 --> 00:40:27.490
give their wealth away
in a productive way.

00:40:30.680 --> 00:40:40.140
So, I have several outside
speakers, and I tried to bring

00:40:40.140 --> 00:40:44.230
in people that are connected
to the world

00:40:44.230 --> 00:40:45.230
in a positive way.

00:40:45.230 --> 00:40:48.560
I'm trying to bring in
inspirations for you as

00:40:48.560 --> 00:40:50.550
outside speakers.

00:40:50.550 --> 00:40:53.060
And they're people who
are in finance

00:40:53.060 --> 00:40:54.990
but who are not selfish.

00:40:54.990 --> 00:41:00.410
They may be rich but they
are good people.

00:41:00.410 --> 00:41:03.380
So, the first person that I'm
going to bring in, as I've

00:41:03.380 --> 00:41:10.270
done in previous years, is David
Swensen, who is Chief

00:41:10.270 --> 00:41:13.370
Investment Officer for
Yale University.

00:41:13.370 --> 00:41:18.300
Swensen also teaches a course,
Economics 450, with Dean

00:41:18.300 --> 00:41:22.400
Takahashi, which you
might want to take.

00:41:22.400 --> 00:41:26.300
But I have him here just
for one lecture.

00:41:26.300 --> 00:41:32.260
And what Swensen has done is
turn the Yale endowment into a

00:41:32.260 --> 00:41:34.290
huge number.

00:41:34.290 --> 00:41:38.840
He came to Yale in 1985, and
at that time, Yale had less

00:41:38.840 --> 00:41:42.260
than $1 billion in
its endowment.

00:41:42.260 --> 00:41:48.380
Swensen is the most successful
university endowment manager

00:41:48.380 --> 00:41:50.280
of the United States.

00:41:50.280 --> 00:41:58.500
He turned less than $1 billion
into $22.9 in 2008.

00:41:58.500 --> 00:42:03.140
The financial crisis hit and the
endowment fell, but as of

00:42:03.140 --> 00:42:08.070
June of 2010, it was
still 16.7 billion.

00:42:08.070 --> 00:42:13.210
So, he has done so much to
make Yale a success.

00:42:13.210 --> 00:42:14.680
But it matters.

00:42:14.680 --> 00:42:16.660
That's a lot of money.

00:42:16.660 --> 00:42:18.890
And it's all for a good cause.

00:42:18.890 --> 00:42:23.610
Now I say, I believe Swensen
is a good person.

00:42:23.610 --> 00:42:26.570
I think he turned down
opportunities to make much

00:42:26.570 --> 00:42:29.990
more on Wall Street, because
he is known -- and he's

00:42:29.990 --> 00:42:32.150
continually turning
them down --

00:42:32.150 --> 00:42:34.400
as an investment genius.

00:42:34.400 --> 00:42:39.140
He can command huge salaries and
bonuses if he wanted to,

00:42:39.140 --> 00:42:41.790
but he stays here with Yale.

00:42:41.790 --> 00:42:44.450
I don't think that people in
finance are money-grubbers,

00:42:44.450 --> 00:42:48.180
and this is an example
of someone who's not.

00:42:48.180 --> 00:42:55.520
The second speaker I have is
Maurice "Hank" Greenberg, who

00:42:55.520 --> 00:42:58.540
founded AIG.

00:42:58.540 --> 00:43:04.880
It started out in 1962.

00:43:04.880 --> 00:43:10.240
In 1962, he was put in charge
of North American operations

00:43:10.240 --> 00:43:13.410
of the American International
Group, an insurance company,

00:43:13.410 --> 00:43:15.240
which was then failing.

00:43:15.240 --> 00:43:20.540
The head of the company, C.V.
Starr, put him in this to try

00:43:20.540 --> 00:43:23.100
to turn the company around.

00:43:23.100 --> 00:43:27.600
He turned it, over many years
as CEO of AIG, into the

00:43:27.600 --> 00:43:32.100
biggest insurance company
in the world, and he

00:43:32.100 --> 00:43:35.230
ran it until 2005.

00:43:35.230 --> 00:43:37.190
The company -- have you
heard of this, AIG?

00:43:37.190 --> 00:43:38.670
You must have heard of this.

00:43:38.670 --> 00:43:41.710
In the recent financial crisis
it has encountered some

00:43:41.710 --> 00:43:46.230
problems. And, in fact, it was
the biggest bailout of all.

00:43:46.230 --> 00:43:48.210
It was bailed out by the
U.S. government.

00:43:48.210 --> 00:43:50.870
And there's a scandal about
that because the

00:43:50.870 --> 00:43:52.750
bailout was so huge.

00:43:52.750 --> 00:43:54.940
It was in the hundreds
of billions.

00:43:54.940 --> 00:43:57.280
Record-setting bailout.

00:43:57.280 --> 00:44:00.780
And some people are angry
with Greenberg.

00:44:00.780 --> 00:44:03.820
But I think that's completely
unfair, because it all

00:44:03.820 --> 00:44:05.800
happened after he left AIG.

00:44:05.800 --> 00:44:09.670
And the problems were in a
particular unit within AIG

00:44:09.670 --> 00:44:12.990
that he was not really
responsible for.

00:44:12.990 --> 00:44:19.150
But Greenberg is a person who
has, I think, a moral purpose

00:44:19.150 --> 00:44:22.170
that I want to illustrate
for you.

00:44:22.170 --> 00:44:24.040
He's been criticized.

00:44:24.040 --> 00:44:26.750
Anyone who does business on
that scale is going to be

00:44:26.750 --> 00:44:32.320
criticized for being too tough
or too aggressive at times.

00:44:32.320 --> 00:44:38.250
But he's a very involved
person.

00:44:38.250 --> 00:44:42.970
He's the Vice Chairman for the
Council on Foreign Relations,

00:44:42.970 --> 00:44:46.370
which is a think tank that
thinks about the United States

00:44:46.370 --> 00:44:47.730
and its place in the world.

00:44:47.730 --> 00:44:50.520
It's a very important
think tank.

00:44:50.520 --> 00:44:53.400
He's also a major philanthropist
and

00:44:53.400 --> 00:44:54.720
he's given to Yale.

00:44:54.720 --> 00:44:58.420
Notably, he gave the Greenberg
Center, which is right next to

00:44:58.420 --> 00:45:01.830
the Center for Globalization.

00:45:01.830 --> 00:45:05.430
A beautiful new building.

00:45:05.430 --> 00:45:07.260
So, he has agreed to come.

00:45:07.260 --> 00:45:09.540
I'm very pleased to have him.

