00:46:56.030 --> 00:46:58.110
United States.

00:46:58.110 --> 00:47:01.790
And he's doing an interesting
study of the

00:47:01.790 --> 00:47:03.840
pizza delivery industry.

00:47:03.840 --> 00:47:08.480
It sounds funny, but it's an
interesting application of

00:47:08.480 --> 00:47:12.990
economic theory to very
much the real world.

00:47:12.990 --> 00:47:18.140
Bige Kahraman is from Bilkent
University in Turkey, and

00:47:18.140 --> 00:47:20.940
she's interested in Behavioral
Finance.

00:47:20.940 --> 00:47:21.660
That means --

00:47:21.660 --> 00:47:22.870
I should have said this.

00:47:22.870 --> 00:47:24.770
It's also an interest
of this course.

00:47:24.770 --> 00:47:26.790
I've skipped by it
in my notes.

00:47:26.790 --> 00:47:30.390
Behavioral Finance is the
application of psychology,

00:47:30.390 --> 00:47:33.800
sociology, and other social
sciences to finance.

00:47:33.800 --> 00:47:36.760
I don't know how I omitted
mentioning that.

00:47:36.760 --> 00:47:39.870
It's about people in finance
-- well, I didn't really

00:47:39.870 --> 00:47:41.090
completely omit mentioning it.

00:47:41.090 --> 00:47:43.640
You've got the sense that I'm
interested in people.

00:47:43.640 --> 00:47:46.080
But there's been a revolution
in finance

00:47:46.080 --> 00:47:48.320
over the last 20 years.

00:47:48.320 --> 00:47:52.140
Twenty years ago, finance was
thought of in academia as an

00:47:52.140 --> 00:47:54.600
essentially mathematical
discipline,

00:47:54.600 --> 00:47:56.220
that and nothing more.

00:47:56.220 --> 00:47:58.100
Well, maybe I'm exaggerating
a little bit.

00:47:58.100 --> 00:48:01.830
But what's happened since then
is people think of finance as

00:48:01.830 --> 00:48:03.700
involving psychology.

00:48:03.700 --> 00:48:09.300
We have to bring people with
knowledge of human beings in.

00:48:09.300 --> 00:48:16.590
And so, her dissertation topic,
a major theme of it, is

00:48:16.590 --> 00:48:18.250
how mutual funds operate.

00:48:18.250 --> 00:48:21.730
Mutual funds are companies that
offer investment vehicles

00:48:21.730 --> 00:48:25.490
to the general public, and she
finds that the mutual fund

00:48:25.490 --> 00:48:29.890
companies have complicated fee
schedules and they offer

00:48:29.890 --> 00:48:31.930
different choices to people.

00:48:31.930 --> 00:48:34.950
And what sense does this make?

00:48:34.950 --> 00:48:36.820
Why are there all these
different choices?

00:48:36.820 --> 00:48:39.400
You look at the fee schedules
and you think --

00:48:39.400 --> 00:48:41.880
it's just like your cell
phone plan, right?

00:48:41.880 --> 00:48:44.400
It's got different choices and
you don't know which one I

00:48:44.400 --> 00:48:45.540
should take.

00:48:45.540 --> 00:48:47.800
Why are they doing all this?

00:48:47.800 --> 00:48:52.510
Well, she tries to analyze
what's going on and she finds

00:48:52.510 --> 00:48:57.010
that sometimes it seems like
clients are steered toward a

00:48:57.010 --> 00:49:03.490
fee schedule that's really not
in their interest and that the

00:49:03.490 --> 00:49:08.470
mutual fund managers are doing
some things that maybe we

00:49:08.470 --> 00:49:09.940
don't want them to do.

00:49:09.940 --> 00:49:11.530
Maybe it's not ideal.

00:49:11.530 --> 00:49:14.330
They're pushed by competitive
pressures into offering

00:49:14.330 --> 00:49:20.870
products that are a little bit
manipulative of people.

00:49:20.870 --> 00:49:23.410
And her dissertation also brings
up another theme, which

00:49:23.410 --> 00:49:26.150
I thought I perhaps should have
emphasized, that all is

00:49:26.150 --> 00:49:28.790
not well in the financial
world.

00:49:28.790 --> 00:49:30.300
Lots of bad things happen.

00:49:30.300 --> 00:49:34.980
Or not necessarily awful things,
but, you know, not

00:49:34.980 --> 00:49:37.610
socially conscious things.

00:49:37.610 --> 00:49:39.570
And that's why we
need regulators.

00:49:39.570 --> 00:49:40.840
That's another reason
why I brought in

00:49:40.840 --> 00:49:42.100
Laura Cha, by the way.

00:49:42.100 --> 00:49:43.410
She's a regulator.

00:49:43.410 --> 00:49:46.840
I wanted to have a voice from
that side, because I

00:49:46.840 --> 00:49:49.350
personally admire regulators
and think that they have a

00:49:49.350 --> 00:49:53.620
very important function
in our society.

00:49:53.620 --> 00:49:56.190
So, her work fits
more into that

00:49:56.190 --> 00:50:02.110
regulatory side of finance.

00:50:02.110 --> 00:50:07.410
And then, finally, our fourth
teaching assistant is Bin Li

00:50:07.410 --> 00:50:11.040
from Beijing, although he went
to college at University

00:50:11.040 --> 00:50:13.270
College London.

00:50:13.270 --> 00:50:19.340
And he has broad interests
including Leveraged Asset

00:50:19.340 --> 00:50:22.480
Pricing and also Behavioral
Finance.

00:50:22.480 --> 00:50:26.350
So, those are the teaching
assistants.

00:50:26.350 --> 00:50:32.190
So, let me just give a brief
outline of the course.

00:50:32.190 --> 00:50:36.890
There are 20 lectures that I'm
giving in this course.

00:50:39.650 --> 00:50:46.830
This is the first. Let me just
go through what's the content

00:50:46.830 --> 00:50:48.080
of these lectures.

00:50:51.310 --> 00:50:55.040
So, Lecture 2, that would be on
Wednesday of this week, I

00:50:55.040 --> 00:51:01.870
want to talk about the core
concept of risk and also about

00:51:01.870 --> 00:51:03.720
financial crises.

00:51:03.720 --> 00:51:06.520
The one reason why I wanted to
update this course with Open

00:51:06.520 --> 00:51:09.420
Yale this year is, because I
wanted to talk about the

00:51:09.420 --> 00:51:13.720
financial crisis that we've been
through, though I thought

00:51:13.720 --> 00:51:17.130
this lecture would start with
something about the theory of

00:51:17.130 --> 00:51:20.260
probability, but I'm not going
to get into that very much.

00:51:20.260 --> 00:51:22.350
That will be more for
a TA section that

00:51:22.350 --> 00:51:23.690
will come in later.

00:51:23.690 --> 00:51:26.030
But even so, this is not
a probability course.

00:51:26.030 --> 00:51:28.320
I just want to kind of remind
you of the concepts of

00:51:28.320 --> 00:51:29.480
probability.

00:51:29.480 --> 00:51:32.570
And there's a concept of
independent risks.

00:51:32.570 --> 00:51:36.690
If risks are independent you can
diversify away them, and

00:51:36.690 --> 00:51:39.760
you can put together
a portfolio that

00:51:39.760 --> 00:51:42.340
minimizes the risks.

00:51:42.340 --> 00:51:44.660
The law of large numbers says
if you have a lot of

00:51:44.660 --> 00:51:48.120
independent risks, they'll
average out if you have a

00:51:48.120 --> 00:51:50.950
large number of these different
risks in your

00:51:50.950 --> 00:51:53.890
portfolio and there's
no risk left.

00:51:53.890 --> 00:51:55.960
That's if they're independent.

00:51:55.960 --> 00:52:00.410
But in fact, risks are not as
independent as you think, and

00:52:00.410 --> 00:52:03.580
that's one reason why we
had a financial crisis.

00:52:03.580 --> 00:52:06.560
And so, a lot of people were
making plans based on

00:52:06.560 --> 00:52:10.890
portfolio theory in finance,
but the plans assumed that

00:52:10.890 --> 00:52:13.900
there won't be a crisis, that
maybe one of our investments

00:52:13.900 --> 00:52:16.810
will go bad, but they can't all
go bad or a large number

00:52:16.810 --> 00:52:18.130
of them can't go bad.

00:52:18.130 --> 00:52:20.270
So, that was a failure
of the independence

00:52:20.270 --> 00:52:23.850
assumption in finance.

00:52:23.850 --> 00:52:29.000
That failure created the
financial crisis that we've

00:52:29.000 --> 00:52:29.900
been through.

00:52:29.900 --> 00:52:35.160
It was a near miss onto another
Great Depression.

00:52:35.160 --> 00:52:38.250
The financial crisis that
began in 1929 --

00:52:38.250 --> 00:52:40.840
I'll talk about that briefly
in that lecture --

00:52:40.840 --> 00:52:46.640
started with the stock market
crash of 1929 and the economy

00:52:46.640 --> 00:52:52.220
spiraled down until 1933.

00:52:52.220 --> 00:52:55.540
It just kept getting
worse and worse.

00:52:55.540 --> 00:52:58.690
More and more bankruptcies,
more and more layoffs.

00:52:58.690 --> 00:53:04.640
So, by 1933, 25% of the U.S.
population was unemployed.

00:53:04.640 --> 00:53:07.860
And it wasn't just the U.S.,
it was all over the world.

00:53:07.860 --> 00:53:09.890
It was a horrible crisis.

00:53:09.890 --> 00:53:15.280
And we didn't get over that
crisis until World War II.

00:53:15.280 --> 00:53:17.490
It's like we couldn't
get out of it.

00:53:17.490 --> 00:53:21.870
The crisis got so bad that
nobody in the world could

00:53:21.870 --> 00:53:23.970
figure out what to do.

00:53:23.970 --> 00:53:27.370
And I think that part of the
reason we had World War II was

00:53:27.370 --> 00:53:31.040
because of the anxieties and
animosities caused by this

00:53:31.040 --> 00:53:33.000
massive unemployment.

00:53:33.000 --> 00:53:36.750
But we got out of it because
World War II created a huge

00:53:36.750 --> 00:53:38.020
stimulus program.

00:53:38.020 --> 00:53:39.670
I mean, they drafted
all the unemployed

00:53:39.670 --> 00:53:40.910
and made them fight.

00:53:40.910 --> 00:53:44.560
What an awful outcome, but
that's what happened.

00:53:44.560 --> 00:53:46.120
It's terrible.

00:53:46.120 --> 00:53:49.940
And so, this time we
saw the beginnings

00:53:49.940 --> 00:53:51.180
of a similar crisis.

00:53:51.180 --> 00:53:54.710
We saw crashes in the stock
market and the real estate

00:53:54.710 --> 00:53:57.430
market, we saw bankruptcies
appearing,

00:53:57.430 --> 00:53:59.870
we saw runs on banks.

00:53:59.870 --> 00:54:05.210
And this time the Government
decided on a controversial

00:54:05.210 --> 00:54:06.870
bailout package.

00:54:06.870 --> 00:54:11.620
And so, Ben Bernanke and Mervyn
King and other central

00:54:11.620 --> 00:54:14.650
bankers and government
policymakers around the world

00:54:14.650 --> 00:54:17.530
had the idea that we can't
let it happen the

00:54:17.530 --> 00:54:19.150
same way this time.

00:54:19.150 --> 00:54:22.500
So, there was massive bailouts,
controversial

00:54:22.500 --> 00:54:26.160
bailouts, because they seemed
to be unfair to many people.

00:54:26.160 --> 00:54:28.360
So, it's a huge and
interesting story.

00:54:28.360 --> 00:54:31.470
I've written three books, by
the way, about this crisis.

00:54:31.470 --> 00:54:33.400
Well, two of them
with co-authors.

00:54:33.400 --> 00:54:36.760
So, it's something that
fascinates me.

00:54:36.760 --> 00:54:39.610
But I don't want to dwell on
it too much in this course,

00:54:39.610 --> 00:54:44.770
because I'm hopeful that it will
heal itself and we can

00:54:44.770 --> 00:54:46.030
put it behind us.

00:54:46.030 --> 00:54:49.000
And the financial crisis doesn't
call into question the

00:54:49.000 --> 00:54:51.020
basic principles of finance.

00:54:51.020 --> 00:54:52.940
Not in my mind.

00:54:52.940 --> 00:54:57.170
The vulnerability to a crash
that we see in financial

00:54:57.170 --> 00:55:00.780
markets is like the same thing
as the vulnerability to crash

00:55:00.780 --> 00:55:02.080
of airplanes.

00:55:02.080 --> 00:55:03.930
Airplanes crash from
time to time.

00:55:03.930 --> 00:55:06.090
You must know that when
you get on one.

00:55:06.090 --> 00:55:09.150
But that doesn't mean we
shouldn't have airplanes.

00:55:09.150 --> 00:55:14.290
And I think the financial system
is advancing in the

00:55:14.290 --> 00:55:18.960
world with such speed and such
impressiveness that this

00:55:18.960 --> 00:55:23.390
crisis is just a blip on the
screen of that, and not

00:55:23.390 --> 00:55:28.230
something I think we should
worry too much about.

00:55:28.230 --> 00:55:30.510
The third lecture is about
technology and

00:55:30.510 --> 00:55:34.190
invention in finance.

00:55:34.190 --> 00:55:39.690
Finance is a technology just
like engineering or mechanical

00:55:39.690 --> 00:55:40.630
engineering.

00:55:40.630 --> 00:55:44.590
It has principles, it has
techniques, and it involves

00:55:44.590 --> 00:55:46.740
inventing of details.

00:55:46.740 --> 00:55:50.170
That is, financial institutions
are complicated.

00:55:50.170 --> 00:55:52.930
They're complicated in the
same way automobiles or

00:55:52.930 --> 00:55:57.160
airplanes or nuclear
power reactors are.

00:55:57.160 --> 00:55:59.460
You can see this complexity,
if you read some of the

00:55:59.460 --> 00:56:03.440
documents that are associated
with the modern corporation.

00:56:03.440 --> 00:56:04.950
There's a lot there.

00:56:04.950 --> 00:56:09.530
And the way the cash flows are
divided up among different

00:56:09.530 --> 00:56:14.170
people, involving options and
derivatives and other

00:56:14.170 --> 00:56:17.130
complicated financial
instruments, are part of the

00:56:17.130 --> 00:56:18.200
technology.

00:56:18.200 --> 00:56:21.840
And this technology is
advancing, and it will advance

00:56:21.840 --> 00:56:25.040
a lot over the time
of your career.

00:56:25.040 --> 00:56:29.000
I don't have an ability to
predict the future with any

00:56:29.000 --> 00:56:32.490
accuracy, but I want to try to
think about what we can say

00:56:32.490 --> 00:56:33.570
about the future.

00:56:33.570 --> 00:56:37.710
I wrote a book in 2003 called
The New Financial Order, and

00:56:37.710 --> 00:56:39.720
it was my take on the future.

00:56:39.720 --> 00:56:41.870
But the problem is nobody
really knows

00:56:41.870 --> 00:56:43.120
the future very well.

00:56:47.800 --> 00:56:50.920
You kind of have to just invent
it or dream about what

00:56:50.920 --> 00:56:52.170
it might be like.

00:56:52.170 --> 00:56:52.850
That's what I did.

00:56:52.850 --> 00:56:56.360
I kind of thought about
principles of financial theory

00:56:56.360 --> 00:57:00.010
and where they might go with
the advance of information

00:57:00.010 --> 00:57:04.180
technology and the globalization
of the world.

00:57:04.180 --> 00:57:07.390
So, I have just a chapter
from that for that

00:57:07.390 --> 00:57:10.360
section of the course.

00:57:10.360 --> 00:57:14.820
Then, Lecture 4 is about
portfolio diversification, how

00:57:14.820 --> 00:57:16.960
risks are spread.

00:57:16.960 --> 00:57:18.960
And we'll talk briefly
about the Capital

00:57:18.960 --> 00:57:20.340
Asset Pricing Model.

00:57:20.340 --> 00:57:23.170
Now again, the Capital Asset
Pricing Model is a

00:57:23.170 --> 00:57:28.420
mathematical theory of
diversification.

00:57:28.420 --> 00:57:31.240
A very important theory, and
it's something that John

00:57:31.240 --> 00:57:36.570
Geanakoplos will cover with more
rigor in Econ 251 that I

00:57:36.570 --> 00:57:38.650
already mentioned.

00:57:38.650 --> 00:57:41.810
But for me, I will talk briefly
about the capital

00:57:41.810 --> 00:57:44.370
asset pricing model, and one
of our teaching assistants

00:57:44.370 --> 00:57:47.300
will give a section on it.

00:57:47.300 --> 00:57:49.460
But I want to also think about,
since this is a course

00:57:49.460 --> 00:57:52.000
about the real world, I want
to think about financial

00:57:52.000 --> 00:57:56.230
institutions, and so many of our
institutions are offering

00:57:56.230 --> 00:57:59.900
diversification one
way or another.

00:57:59.900 --> 00:58:02.640
And so, again, I wanted to
talk about the real world

00:58:02.640 --> 00:58:04.230
component of this.

00:58:04.230 --> 00:58:09.130
The fifth lecture is
about insurance.

00:58:09.130 --> 00:58:14.920
And the insurance industry
developed over the centuries.

00:58:14.920 --> 00:58:16.550
It goes, actually, all the
way back to Ancient

00:58:16.550 --> 00:58:19.750
Rome, but only minimally.

00:58:19.750 --> 00:58:24.200
People didn't have the concepts
until the 1600s when

00:58:24.200 --> 00:58:26.220
probability theory
was invented.

00:58:26.220 --> 00:58:29.060
There was an intuitive concept
that, sure, I could start an

00:58:29.060 --> 00:58:32.120
insurance company, I could put
together a lot of insurance

00:58:32.120 --> 00:58:36.920
policies and charge for them,
and probably I won't --

00:58:36.920 --> 00:58:40.060
you just have intuitive sense
about law of large number or

00:58:40.060 --> 00:58:41.170
independence of risks.

00:58:41.170 --> 00:58:44.080
Probably, I'll be OK and
I can make good on the

00:58:44.080 --> 00:58:45.400
policies that I wrote.

00:58:45.400 --> 00:58:46.790
But it was never clear until

00:58:46.790 --> 00:58:49.220
probability theory was developed.

00:58:49.220 --> 00:58:51.870
Since then, it's been growing
and it's becoming a bigger and

00:58:51.870 --> 00:58:53.490
bigger part of our lives.

00:58:53.490 --> 00:58:59.440
And I think that insurance
is actually a lifesaver.

00:58:59.440 --> 00:59:01.270
I'll give you one example.

00:59:01.270 --> 00:59:03.885
You note that in the earthquake
in Haiti --

00:59:06.820 --> 00:59:10.890
what was that, about
a year ago?

00:59:10.890 --> 00:59:15.020
There was a tremendous loss of
life, but the earthquake in

00:59:15.020 --> 00:59:20.360
San Francisco decades earlier
was of the same magnitude and

00:59:20.360 --> 00:59:23.050
had very little loss of life.

00:59:23.050 --> 00:59:27.650
Also, the loss suffered by
people in terms of destruction

00:59:27.650 --> 00:59:31.000
of their homes and their office
buildings was vastly

00:59:31.000 --> 00:59:32.190
higher in Haiti.

00:59:32.190 --> 00:59:35.410
Well, it turns out that Haiti,
a less developed country,

00:59:35.410 --> 00:59:39.790
didn't have much of the modern
insurance industry, so that

00:59:39.790 --> 00:59:42.680
people were uninsured against
risk of collapse of their

00:59:42.680 --> 00:59:46.180
structure and you didn't have
insurance industries going in

00:59:46.180 --> 00:59:48.670
and policing building codes.

00:59:48.670 --> 00:59:52.110
If the insurance company is
liable to the risk then they

00:59:52.110 --> 00:59:56.400
go in and say, we won't insure
you unless you fix this.

00:59:56.400 --> 00:59:59.920
Since it didn't happen,
so many people died.

00:59:59.920 --> 01:00:01.980
I think that Haiti
will come along.

01:00:01.980 --> 01:00:04.290
There is already a Caribbean
insurance

01:00:04.290 --> 01:00:06.490
initiative that was starting.

01:00:06.490 --> 01:00:11.660
We want to see the developing
world get these institutions.

01:00:11.660 --> 01:00:14.650
I want to try to give a sense
of the reality of that, that

01:00:14.650 --> 01:00:17.270
we tend to think of Haiti as
an opportunity for our

01:00:17.270 --> 01:00:21.660
charity, and a lot of us gave
money to help these people.

01:00:21.660 --> 01:00:26.620
But, you know, charity doesn't
work on a big enough scale.

01:00:26.620 --> 01:00:29.030
Going around to people on the
street and asking them to give

01:00:29.030 --> 01:00:33.100
money to help the Haitian
earthquake victims, it doesn't

01:00:33.100 --> 01:00:34.950
amount to a lot.

01:00:34.950 --> 01:00:37.970
What really becomes big and
important is the insurance

01:00:37.970 --> 01:00:40.250
industry, which is doing
the same thing

01:00:40.250 --> 01:00:42.410
as a business model.

01:00:42.410 --> 01:00:47.730
And that's the real world and
it matters enormously.

01:00:47.730 --> 01:00:51.760
The sixth lecture is about
efficient markets.

01:00:51.760 --> 01:00:57.950
This is about a theory that
developed in the 1960s, that

01:00:57.950 --> 01:01:01.480
financial markets are
wonderfully perfect.

01:01:01.480 --> 01:01:03.740
I'm saying I'm a little bit
skeptical of this theory,

01:01:03.740 --> 01:01:05.850
although I think it has
an element of truth.

01:01:05.850 --> 01:01:10.790
Efficient Markets Theory is the
idea that you really can't

01:01:10.790 --> 01:01:13.380
make money by trading in
financial markets, because the

01:01:13.380 --> 01:01:19.060
markets are so competitive that
price is always pushed to

01:01:19.060 --> 01:01:22.790
an optimal level that
incorporates all information

01:01:22.790 --> 01:01:25.510
that anyone could ever have
about the security.

01:01:25.510 --> 01:01:31.500
And the theory has been that
it's hopeless to try to invest

01:01:31.500 --> 01:01:33.680
and beat the market.

01:01:33.680 --> 01:01:36.090
Well, I think there's an element
of truth to that but

01:01:36.090 --> 01:01:39.600
it's not quite true, and people
like David Swensen are

01:01:39.600 --> 01:01:44.640
counterexamples, that it is
possible for professional

01:01:44.640 --> 01:01:47.530
money managers to
beat the market.

01:01:47.530 --> 01:01:52.735
And that's something I want to
think about and talk about in

01:01:52.735 --> 01:01:53.940
that lecture.

01:01:53.940 --> 01:01:55.920
Lecture 7 is about
debt markets.

01:01:59.360 --> 01:02:03.920
We have a lot of money
that's lent.

01:02:03.920 --> 01:02:07.430
The Federal Reserve manages
these markets.

01:02:07.430 --> 01:02:13.290
They try to coordinate the
markets through open market

01:02:13.290 --> 01:02:15.680
operations and through
what now is called

01:02:15.680 --> 01:02:18.570
Quantitative Easing.

01:02:18.570 --> 01:02:22.030
But the markets are huge
and international.

01:02:22.030 --> 01:02:25.150
They involve errors
that people make.

01:02:25.150 --> 01:02:28.650
A lot of people get overly
indebted and make mistakes

01:02:28.650 --> 01:02:30.760
over their lives.

01:02:30.760 --> 01:02:33.580
But they also offer
opportunities, that debt

01:02:33.580 --> 01:02:35.550
markets are fundamental
to the things we want

01:02:35.550 --> 01:02:36.910
to do in our lives.

01:02:36.910 --> 01:02:40.020
For example, when you are a
little bit older, many of you

01:02:40.020 --> 01:02:42.720
will want to buy
a house, right?

01:02:42.720 --> 01:02:45.120
But you won't be in that point
in the life cycle when you

01:02:45.120 --> 01:02:47.820
have the money to buy a
house, most of you,

01:02:47.820 --> 01:02:48.800
so you'll be borrowing.

01:02:48.800 --> 01:02:49.620
It's elementary.

01:02:49.620 --> 01:02:50.990
You take out a mortgage.

01:02:50.990 --> 01:02:51.970
That seems obvious.

01:02:51.970 --> 01:02:54.960
But still today in many
countries of the world, the

01:02:54.960 --> 01:02:57.250
mortgage market is not
very developed, and

01:02:57.250 --> 01:02:58.980
you can't do that.

01:02:58.980 --> 01:03:01.580
So, there's a good side
to borrowing as

01:03:01.580 --> 01:03:02.330
well as a bad side.

01:03:02.330 --> 01:03:04.990
I want to put it
in perspective.

01:03:04.990 --> 01:03:06.300
We've got our review session.

01:03:06.300 --> 01:03:08.440
We'll talk a little bit,
somewhat, with one of our

01:03:08.440 --> 01:03:12.750
teaching assistants about
the mathematics of debt.

01:03:12.750 --> 01:03:15.880
Lecture 8 will be about
the stock market.

01:03:15.880 --> 01:03:18.790
Again, I think of the stock
market not as something that

01:03:18.790 --> 01:03:19.610
we're going to beat.

01:03:19.610 --> 01:03:25.730
I think it's something that is
an invention to motivate

01:03:25.730 --> 01:03:28.170
people to get people
working together.

01:03:28.170 --> 01:03:31.730
So, the basic idea of a stock
investment: You and your

01:03:31.730 --> 01:03:34.890
friends want to set
up a company, OK?

01:03:34.890 --> 01:03:35.670
How do you do that?

01:03:35.670 --> 01:03:38.090
Well, the company needs
money to start.

01:03:38.090 --> 01:03:40.170
So, somebody's got to
contribute capital.

01:03:40.170 --> 01:03:42.670
Well, some of you have more
money to contribute than

01:03:42.670 --> 01:03:45.720
others, so you should have a
bigger share in the company.

01:03:45.720 --> 01:03:48.320
Some of you have no money at all
to contribute, but you're

01:03:48.320 --> 01:03:50.450
going to contribute your
time and energy.

01:03:50.450 --> 01:03:53.140
So, you want to give a share in
the company to these other

01:03:53.140 --> 01:03:56.690
people as well in order
to incentivize them.

01:03:56.690 --> 01:04:01.620
So, you devise a whole scheme
to set up a company that

01:04:01.620 --> 01:04:03.650
involves the creation
of stock.

01:04:03.650 --> 01:04:06.490
And then you start trading the
stock and then it gets all the

01:04:06.490 --> 01:04:07.230
more interesting.

01:04:07.230 --> 01:04:10.050
And then there are options on
these stock certificates.

01:04:10.050 --> 01:04:11.440
But it's all for a purpose.

01:04:11.440 --> 01:04:15.450
The purpose is to make some
enterprise happen.

01:04:15.450 --> 01:04:19.090
And it really is important
that we have these

01:04:19.090 --> 01:04:22.780
institutions, and if you don't
have them, your little group

01:04:22.780 --> 01:04:24.870
trying to do something is
going to fall apart.

01:04:24.870 --> 01:04:26.990
Someone's going to get angry
and leave. It's just

01:04:26.990 --> 01:04:28.240
not going to work.

01:04:28.240 --> 01:04:29.860
And so, I think of
the stock market

01:04:29.860 --> 01:04:31.550
as doing these functions.

01:04:31.550 --> 01:04:34.270
Now I know Karl Marx said he
thought it was a big casino,

01:04:34.270 --> 01:04:36.180
but we're not communists here.

01:04:36.180 --> 01:04:39.790
This is about modern finance.

01:04:39.790 --> 01:04:43.010
Lecture 9 is about
real estate.

01:04:43.010 --> 01:04:44.570
Another fascination for me.

01:04:44.570 --> 01:04:47.580
I've been working for years
about real estate.

01:04:47.580 --> 01:04:50.950
And, in fact, with my colleague
Karl Case, we have

01:04:50.950 --> 01:04:54.470
our own home price indices
called the Standard and Poor

01:04:54.470 --> 01:04:56.080
Case-Shiller Home
Price Indices.

01:04:56.080 --> 01:04:58.240
We'll talk about those.

01:04:58.240 --> 01:05:01.340
But it's really important for
this crisis that we've just

01:05:01.340 --> 01:05:05.390
seen, because the financial
crisis was caused

01:05:05.390 --> 01:05:11.160
substantially by a bubble in
home prices, I believe, a

01:05:11.160 --> 01:05:14.380
psychologically induced
excitement or euphoria about

01:05:14.380 --> 01:05:17.550
home prices in the United States
and in other countries

01:05:17.550 --> 01:05:20.210
that collapsed around 2006.

01:05:20.210 --> 01:05:23.940
These bubbles are restarting
in other parts of the world

01:05:23.940 --> 01:05:25.030
more recently.

01:05:25.030 --> 01:05:29.940
And the real estate market is
getting very speculative and

01:05:29.940 --> 01:05:32.210
psychological, I believe.

01:05:32.210 --> 01:05:35.960
And the outlook right now for
the economy hinges on how

01:05:35.960 --> 01:05:44.120
these markets behave. So, that
will be, I think, an important

01:05:44.120 --> 01:05:46.130
lecture for this course.

01:05:46.130 --> 01:05:48.950
Lecture 10 is about Behavioral
Finance.

01:05:48.950 --> 01:05:50.510
It's about psychology
in finance.

01:05:50.510 --> 01:05:51.640
I talked about that.

01:05:51.640 --> 01:05:55.930
It's another long-standing
interest of mine to try to

01:05:55.930 --> 01:06:01.370
incorporate psychology
into our theory.

01:06:01.370 --> 01:06:06.200
So, lecture 12 is about banking,
multiple expansion of

01:06:06.200 --> 01:06:11.390
credit, the money multiplier,
and bank regulation, which is

01:06:11.390 --> 01:06:14.820
something that is a fascinating
topic, because we

01:06:14.820 --> 01:06:16.620
almost lost our banking
system.

01:06:16.620 --> 01:06:19.510
We had to bail them
out massively.

01:06:19.510 --> 01:06:21.770
We have international
accords now.

01:06:21.770 --> 01:06:25.300
Notably, a new one just came
out called Basel III from

01:06:25.300 --> 01:06:27.850
Basel, which is the city in
Switzerland, and it was

01:06:27.850 --> 01:06:30.790
endorsed by the G-20
countries at their

01:06:30.790 --> 01:06:33.210
Korean meeting in Seoul.

01:06:33.210 --> 01:06:38.000
So, we're seeing a change in
bank regulation that will, we

01:06:38.000 --> 01:06:42.050
hope, prevent another
crisis like the one

01:06:42.050 --> 01:06:44.420
we just went through.

01:06:44.420 --> 01:06:47.223
Lecture 13 is about forwards
and futures markets.

01:06:50.380 --> 01:06:54.400
Forward markets are markets for
contracts that deliver in

01:06:54.400 --> 01:06:56.610
the future.

01:06:56.610 --> 01:07:00.290
Over-the-counter contracts,
they're called, that are done

01:07:00.290 --> 01:07:04.590
one on one between parties
with the help of

01:07:04.590 --> 01:07:06.590
an investment bank.

01:07:06.590 --> 01:07:10.010
Or futures contracts, which
are traded on organized

01:07:10.010 --> 01:07:15.700
futures exchanges, like the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.

01:07:15.700 --> 01:07:19.420
I have some involvement with
this, because we worked with

01:07:19.420 --> 01:07:21.760
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange
to create a futures

01:07:21.760 --> 01:07:24.810
market for single-family
homes using the S&amp;P

01:07:24.810 --> 01:07:26.160
Case-Shiller Index.

01:07:26.160 --> 01:07:28.780
So, I'm involved in this.

01:07:28.780 --> 01:07:33.930
And we have that market
functioning at a rather low

01:07:33.930 --> 01:07:35.720
level, but it is functioning
and it seems

01:07:35.720 --> 01:07:37.250
to be growing lately.

01:07:37.250 --> 01:07:39.600
I'm hopeful for that market.

01:07:39.600 --> 01:07:42.440
Lecture 14 is about
options markets.

01:07:42.440 --> 01:07:47.060
These are most typically stock
options, which are contracts

01:07:47.060 --> 01:07:51.510
that allow you to purchase a
share of a stock or to sell a

01:07:51.510 --> 01:07:54.010
share at a pre-specified
price.

01:07:54.010 --> 01:07:56.250
These are traded on
options exchanges.

01:07:56.250 --> 01:07:58.450
They have a price that
goes up and down.

01:07:58.450 --> 01:08:03.110
This is an example of a
derivative contract that

01:08:03.110 --> 01:08:07.040
injects a lot of complexity
into financial theory.

01:08:07.040 --> 01:08:10.590
Lecture 15 is about
monetary policy.

01:08:10.590 --> 01:08:12.790
It's about the central
banks of the world.

01:08:12.790 --> 01:08:16.770
For example, our central bank,
called the Federal Reserve in

01:08:16.770 --> 01:08:18.210
the United States.

01:08:18.210 --> 01:08:23.000
And it's about what they do
and how they help prevent

01:08:23.000 --> 01:08:25.920
crises like the one
we've just seen.

01:08:25.920 --> 01:08:27.020
They did help prevent it.

01:08:27.020 --> 01:08:29.590
I think they staved
off disaster.

01:08:29.590 --> 01:08:32.650
Lecture 16 is about investment
banking.

01:08:32.650 --> 01:08:34.720
I know this is of great
interest, because we place a

01:08:34.720 --> 01:08:38.740
lot of students in good jobs
in investment banking.

01:08:38.740 --> 01:08:44.240
Companies like Goldman Sachs,
the most talked about one.

01:08:44.240 --> 01:08:48.400
Investment bankers help
companies raise capital, issue

01:08:48.400 --> 01:08:51.920
securities, retire securities.

01:08:51.920 --> 01:08:54.330
And we're going to talk about
how they're regulated.

01:08:54.330 --> 01:08:56.940
And I didn't mention Dodd-Frank,
by the way, but we

01:08:56.940 --> 01:09:00.830
have a new bill that just passed
in July in the United

01:09:00.830 --> 01:09:04.980
States that changes the
regulatory structure for

01:09:04.980 --> 01:09:07.060
investment banks and a whole
array of financial

01:09:07.060 --> 01:09:08.110
institutions.

01:09:08.110 --> 01:09:09.500
And I want to talk about that.

01:09:12.380 --> 01:09:17.660
The European Parliament has
created a number of new laws

01:09:17.660 --> 01:09:20.780
and organizations that somewhat
resemble Dodd-Frank.

01:09:20.780 --> 01:09:23.660
And other countries have also
done financial regulation

01:09:23.660 --> 01:09:26.550
reform that affects investment
banking and

01:09:26.550 --> 01:09:28.350
other aspects of finance.

01:09:28.350 --> 01:09:30.480
It's extremely complicated.

01:09:30.480 --> 01:09:34.290
I don't want to give you too
many details but I want to

01:09:34.290 --> 01:09:37.510
give you some sense of the
revolution that we're seeing.

01:09:37.510 --> 01:09:40.640
Lecture 17 is about professional
money managers

01:09:40.640 --> 01:09:44.860
like David Swensen, people
who manage portfolios.

01:09:44.860 --> 01:09:47.190
You don't have to be a
billionaire to manage a

01:09:47.190 --> 01:09:48.900
billion-dollar portfolio.

01:09:48.900 --> 01:09:51.430
In fact, some of you may be
doing it sooner than you

01:09:51.430 --> 01:09:54.700
realize if you get the
right kind of job.

01:09:54.700 --> 01:09:58.070
Managing a portfolio means
managing the risks, putting

01:09:58.070 --> 01:09:59.320
them in the right places.

01:10:04.240 --> 01:10:08.360
You think of institutional
investors, big money managers,

01:10:08.360 --> 01:10:10.400
as just trying to make money.

01:10:10.400 --> 01:10:14.920
But when you get into that field
you realize that you

01:10:14.920 --> 01:10:18.350
have power as an institutional
investor.

01:10:18.350 --> 01:10:21.090
When you own a big share of some
company, you can go to

01:10:21.090 --> 01:10:24.380
the board meeting and talk
to these people, or the

01:10:24.380 --> 01:10:27.850
stockholders' meeting, and you
will get heard if you own 10%

01:10:27.850 --> 01:10:29.400
of the shares of a company.

01:10:29.400 --> 01:10:31.890
Then you suddenly realize that
you are a steward of the

01:10:31.890 --> 01:10:35.540
public interest. And I think
institutional investors are

01:10:35.540 --> 01:10:37.490
recognizing that
more and more.

01:10:37.490 --> 01:10:41.290
Lecture 18 is about exchanges,
brokers, dealers,

01:10:41.290 --> 01:10:44.420
clearinghouses, like the New
York Stock Exchange or the

01:10:44.420 --> 01:10:46.370
London Stock Exchange.

01:10:46.370 --> 01:10:48.920
They are proliferating
around the world.

01:10:48.920 --> 01:10:52.910
Whereas there were just a few 30
years ago, now almost every

01:10:52.910 --> 01:10:55.480
country has a stock
exchange and a

01:10:55.480 --> 01:10:57.390
complicated list of exchanges.

01:10:57.390 --> 01:11:00.050
They're increasingly electronic,
they have

01:11:00.050 --> 01:11:03.740
interesting new features, like
microsecond trading that's

01:11:03.740 --> 01:11:07.270
going on, computers trading
with other computers.

01:11:07.270 --> 01:11:10.110
We'll talk about where
this is going.

01:11:10.110 --> 01:11:15.070
Lecture 19 is about public
and nonprofit finance.

01:11:15.070 --> 01:11:16.650
So, I think this is
very important.

01:11:16.650 --> 01:11:19.760
Nonprofit finance would include
organizations like

01:11:19.760 --> 01:11:23.720
Yale University, or churches
and charities and

01:11:23.720 --> 01:11:25.140
other things like that.

01:11:25.140 --> 01:11:28.300
But I'm also including in this
lecture public finance.

01:11:28.300 --> 01:11:31.350
And that means governments
financing projects.

01:11:31.350 --> 01:11:34.750
So, for example, you take it for
granted that our city here

01:11:34.750 --> 01:11:39.100
of New Haven has roads,
it has schools, it has

01:11:39.100 --> 01:11:40.720
sewers, it has water.

01:11:40.720 --> 01:11:43.100
All this kind of comes without
you even asking.

01:11:43.100 --> 01:11:45.640
But all of these things
had to be financed.

01:11:45.640 --> 01:11:48.840
And the City of New Haven, like
other cities, is issuing

01:11:48.840 --> 01:11:52.080
debt and it's a complicated
business.

01:11:52.080 --> 01:11:54.940
I want to get you into some
of the details, because it

01:11:54.940 --> 01:11:57.520
matters, because this is how
you make things happen.

01:11:57.520 --> 01:12:01.710
You can go to your city
government and you can propose

01:12:01.710 --> 01:12:04.840
that they issue revenue bonds
to start some new product.

01:12:04.840 --> 01:12:05.760
You would know --

01:12:05.760 --> 01:12:08.190
that's what I want you to do,
is to know how these things

01:12:08.190 --> 01:12:11.020
are done, so that it's
not just imagination,

01:12:11.020 --> 01:12:13.330
you can make it happen.

01:12:13.330 --> 01:12:14.810
And also nonprofits.

01:12:14.810 --> 01:12:18.160
I want you to understand that
you can set up your own

01:12:18.160 --> 01:12:21.230
nonprofits, and there's a lot
of advantages to doing that.

01:12:21.230 --> 01:12:24.630
That's an organization that has
a financial structure but

01:12:24.630 --> 01:12:26.070
no shareholders.

01:12:26.070 --> 01:12:27.400
Nobody takes home the money.

01:12:27.400 --> 01:12:29.590
It all goes to some cause.

01:12:29.590 --> 01:12:34.000
And, finally, my last lecture,
Lecture 20, I'm calling it

01:12:34.000 --> 01:12:37.380
''Finding your Purpose in
Finance.'' I just want to come

01:12:37.380 --> 01:12:42.720
back in the last lecture to the
idea that this is a course

01:12:42.720 --> 01:12:44.900
not about making money.

01:12:44.900 --> 01:12:47.840
I don't want you to give a
billion dollars to your

01:12:47.840 --> 01:12:51.490
children and grandchildren,
which they will then squander

01:12:51.490 --> 01:12:53.690
in conspicuous consumption.

01:12:53.690 --> 01:12:58.030
The idea is a moral purpose.

01:12:58.030 --> 01:13:02.200
And that's one thing I wanted to
try to convey, partly with

01:13:02.200 --> 01:13:04.580
outside speakers, maybe with
other examples that I can

01:13:04.580 --> 01:13:11.095
give, that I think that many
people who are wealthy and who

01:13:11.095 --> 01:13:15.900
have succeeded in finance
really don't care about

01:13:15.900 --> 01:13:17.840
spending the money
on themselves.

01:13:17.840 --> 01:13:19.510
They really do have a purpose.

01:13:19.510 --> 01:13:22.480
And even if that's not
true of many of them.

01:13:22.480 --> 01:13:24.660
There's an interesting book by
Robert Frank, I don't have it

01:13:24.660 --> 01:13:27.490
on the reading list, called
Richistan, who talks about

01:13:27.490 --> 01:13:29.740
what wealthy people are
like these days.

01:13:29.740 --> 01:13:33.020
And if you read his book
sometimes they are

01:13:33.020 --> 01:13:36.960
disgustingly rich and spending
the money on silly things.

01:13:36.960 --> 01:13:41.610
But there is an idea among many
of them that they are

01:13:41.610 --> 01:13:45.630
going to do their good
things for the world.

01:13:48.840 --> 01:13:50.900
Because I think many of you will
do these things, I want

01:13:50.900 --> 01:13:59.470
to think about the purpose that
you'll find in finance.

01:13:59.470 --> 01:14:02.060
So, that's just the
closing thought.

01:14:02.060 --> 01:14:05.530
I'll see you again
on Wednesday.

01:14:05.530 --> 01:14:09.510
But the closing thought is that
this is about making your

01:14:09.510 --> 01:14:12.550
purposes happen.

01:14:12.550 --> 01:14:13.800
OK.

